# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: image-captioning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] In machine learning, **attention** is a method that determines the importance of each component in a sequence relative to the other components in that sequence.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] In natural language processing, importance is represented by "soft" weights assigned to each word in a sentence.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] More generally, attention encodes vectors called token embeddings across a fixed-width sequence that can range from tens to millions of tokens in size.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Unlike "hard" weights, which are computed during the backwards training pass, "soft" weights exist only in the forward pass and therefore change with every step of the input.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Earlier designs implemented the attention mechanism in a serial recurrent neural network (RNN) language translation system, but a more recent design, namely the transformer, removed the slower sequential RNN and relied more heavily on the faster parallel attention scheme.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Inspired by ideas about attention in humans, the attention mechanism was developed to address the weaknesses of using information from the hidden layers of recurrent neural networks.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Recurrent neural networks favor information contained in words at the end of a sentence and thus deemed more recent, thereby tending to attenuate the significance and associated predictive weight assigned to information earlier in the sentence.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Attention allows a token equal access to any part of a sentence directly, rather than only through the previous state.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Additional surveys of the attention mechanism in deep learning are provided by Niu et al. and Soydaner.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] The major breakthrough came with self-attention, where each element in the input sequence attends to all others, enabling the model to capture global dependencies.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] This idea was central to the Transformer architecture, which replaced recurrence with attention mechanisms.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] As a result, Transformers became the foundation for models like BERT, T5 and generative pre-trained transformers (GPT).
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] The modern era of machine attention was revitalized by grafting an attention mechanism (Fig 1. orange) to an Encoder-Decoder.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Figure 2 shows the internal step-by-step operation of the attention block (A) in Fig 1.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] The diagram shows the attention forward pass calculating correlations of the word "that" with other words in "See that girl run." Given the right weights from training, the network should be able to identify "girl" as a highly correlated word.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] In translating between languages, alignment is the process of matching words from the source sentence to words of the translated sentence.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Networks that perform verbatim translation without regard to word order would show the highest scores along the (dominant) diagonal of the matrix.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] The off-diagonal dominance shows that the attention mechanism is more nuanced.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Consider an example of translating *I love you* to French.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] On the first pass through the decoder, 94% of the attention weight is on the first English word *I*, so the network offers the word *je*.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] On the second pass of the decoder, 88% of the attention weight is on the third English word *you*, so it offers *t'*.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] On the last pass, 95% of the attention weight is on the second English word *love*, so it offers *aime*.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] In the *I love you* example, the second word *love* is aligned with the third word *aime*.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Sometimes, alignment can be multiple-to-multiple.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] For example, the English phrase *look it up* corresponds to *cherchez-le*.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] For convolutional neural networks, attention mechanisms can be distinguished by the dimension on which they operate, namely: spatial attention, channel attention, or combinations.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] These variants recombine the encoder-side inputs to redistribute those effects to each target output.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Often, a correlation-style matrix of dot products provides the re-weighting coefficients.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] In the figures below, W is the matrix of context attention weights, similar to the formula in Overview section above.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] The size of the attention matrix is proportional to the square of the number of input tokens.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Therefore, when the input is long, calculating the attention matrix requires a lot of GPU memory.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Flash attention is an implementation that reduces the memory needs and increases efficiency without sacrificing accuracy.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] It achieves this by partitioning the attention computation into smaller blocks that fit into the GPU's faster on-chip memory, reducing the need to store large intermediate matrices and thus lowering memory usage while increasing computational efficiency.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] FlexAttention is an attention kernel developed by Meta that allows users to modify attention scores prior to softmax and dynamically chooses the optimal attention algorithm.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Attention is widely used in natural language processing, computer vision, and speech recognition.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] In NLP, it improves context understanding in tasks like question answering and summarization.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] In vision, visual attention helps models focus on relevant image regions, enhancing object detection and image captioning.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] From the original paper on vision transformers (ViT), visualizing attention scores as a heat map (called saliency maps or attention maps) has become an important and routine way to inspect the decision making process of ViT models.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] One can compute the attention maps with respect to any attention head at any layer, while the deeper layers tend to show more semantically meaningful visualization.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Attention rollout is a recursive algorithm to combine attention scores across all layers, by computing the dot product of successive attention maps.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Because vision transformers are typically trained in a self-supervised manner, attention maps are generally not class-sensitive.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] When a classification head is attached to the ViT backbone, class-discriminative attention maps (CDAM) combines attention maps and gradients with respect to the class `[CLS]` token.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Some class-sensitive interpretability methods originally developed for convolutional neural networks can be also applied to ViT, such as GradCAM, which back-propagates the gradients to the outputs of the final attention layer.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Using attention as basis of explanation for the transformers in language and vision is not without debate.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] While some pioneering papers analyzed and framed attention scores as explanations, higher attention scores do not always correlate with greater impact on model performances.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] The matrix Q contains m queries, while matrices $K,V$ jointly contain an *unordered* set of n key-value pairs.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Value vectors in matrix V are weighted using the weights resulting from the softmax operation, so that the rows of the m -by- $d_{v}$ output matrix are confined to the convex hull of the points in $\mathbb {R} ^{d_{v}}$ given by the rows of V .
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] To understand the permutation invariance and permutation equivariance properties of QKV attention, let $A\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times m}$ and $B\in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ be permutation matrices; and $D\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times n}$ an arbitrary matrix.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] These properties are inherited when applying linear transforms to the inputs and outputs of QKV attention blocks.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] For example, a simple self-attention function defined as: $X\mapsto {\text{Attention}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is permutation equivariant with respect to re-ordering the rows of the input matrix X in a non-trivial way, because every row of the output is a function of all the rows of the input.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Similar properties hold for *multi-head attention*, which is defined below.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] The softmax output, also in $\mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}$ is then *lower triangular*, with zeros in all elements above the diagonal.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] The masking ensures that for all $1\leq i<j\leq n$ , row i of the attention output is independent of row j of any of the three input matrices.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] The permutation invariance and equivariance properties of standard QKV attention do not hold for the masked variant.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] The permutation properties of (standard, unmasked) QKV attention apply here also.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] For permutation matrices, $A,B$ : ${\text{MultiHead}}(AQ,BK,BV)=A\,{\text{MultiHead}}(Q,K,V)$ from which we also see that multi-head self-attention: $X\mapsto {\text{MultiHead}}(XT_{q},XT_{k},XT_{v})$ is equivariant with respect to re-ordering of the rows of input matrix X .
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] ${\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}(QWK^{T})V$ where W is a learnable weight matrix.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Self-attention is essentially the same as cross-attention, except that query, key, and value vectors all come from the same model.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] Both encoder and decoder can use self-attention, but with subtle differences.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] For encoder self-attention, we can start with a simple encoder without self-attention, such as an "embedding layer", which simply converts each input word into a vector by a fixed lookup table.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] This gives a sequence of hidden vectors $h_{0},h_{1},\dots$ .
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] This can be applied repeatedly, to obtain a multilayered encoder.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] This is the "encoder self-attention", sometimes called the "all-to-all attention", as the vector at every position can attend to every other.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] For decoder self-attention, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because during the autoregressive decoding process, the decoder cannot attend to future outputs that has yet to be decoded.
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] This can be solved by forcing the attention weights $w_{ij}=0$ for all $i<j$ , called "causal masking".
[src:image-captioning/attention-machine-learning] This attention mechanism is the "causally masked self-attention".
[src:image-captioning/automatic-image-annotation] This method can be regarded as a type of multi-class image classification with a very large number of classes - as large as the vocabulary size.
[src:image-captioning/automatic-image-annotation] Typically, image analysis in the form of extracted feature vectors and the training annotation words are used by machine learning techniques to attempt to automatically apply annotations to new images.
[src:image-captioning/automatic-image-annotation] The first methods learned the correlations between image features and training annotations.
[src:image-captioning/automatic-image-annotation] Subsequently, techniques were developed using machine translation to attempt to translate the textual vocabulary into the 'visual vocabulary,' represented by clustered regions known as *blobs.* Subsequent work has included classification approaches, relevance models, and other related methods.
[src:image-captioning/automatic-image-annotation] The advantages of automatic image annotation versus content-based image retrieval (CBIR) are that queries can be more naturally specified by the user.
[src:image-captioning/automatic-image-annotation] At present, Content-Based Image Retrieval (CBIR) generally requires users to search by image concepts such as color and texture or by finding example queries.
[src:image-captioning/automatic-image-annotation] However, certain image features in example images may override the concept that the user is truly focusing on.
[src:image-captioning/automatic-image-annotation] Traditional methods of image retrieval, such as those used by libraries, have relied on manually annotated images, which is expensive and time-consuming, especially given the large and constantly growing image databases in existence.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The scientific discipline of computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, multi-dimensional data from a 3D scanner, 3D point clouds from LiDaR sensors, or medical scanning devices.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The technological discipline of computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models to the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Subdisciplines of computer vision include scene reconstruction, object detection, event detection, activity recognition, video tracking, object recognition, 3D pose estimation, learning, indexing, motion estimation, visual servoing, 3D scene modeling, and image restoration.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Computer vision is an interdisciplinary field that deals with how computers can be made to gain high-level understanding from digital images or videos.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] From the perspective of engineering, it seeks to automate tasks that the human visual system can do.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] "Computer vision is concerned with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of useful information from a single image or a sequence of images.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] It involves the development of a theoretical and algorithmic basis to achieve automatic visual understanding." As a scientific discipline, computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, or multi-dimensional data from a medical scanner.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] As a technological discipline, computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models for the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Machine vision refers to a systems engineering discipline, especially in the context of factory automation.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] In more recent times, the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] In the late 1960s, computer vision began at universities that were pioneering artificial intelligence.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] It was meant to mimic the human visual system as a stepping stone to endowing robots with intelligent behavior.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] In 1966, it was believed that this could be achieved through an undergraduate summer project, by attaching a camera to a computer and having it "describe what it saw".
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] What distinguished computer vision from the prevalent field of digital image processing at that time was a desire to extract three-dimensional structure from images with the goal of achieving full scene understanding.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The next decade saw studies based on more rigorous mathematical analysis and quantitative aspects of computer vision.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] These include the concept of scale-space, the inference of shape from various cues such as shading, texture and focus, and contour models known as snakes.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Researchers also realized that many of these mathematical concepts could be treated within the same optimization framework as regularization and Markov random fields.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] By the 1990s, some of the previous research topics became more active than others.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Research in projective 3-D reconstructions led to better understanding of camera calibration.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] With the advent of optimization methods for camera calibration, it was realized that a lot of the ideas were already explored in bundle adjustment theory from the field of photogrammetry.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] This led to methods for sparse 3-D reconstructions of scenes from multiple images.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Progress was made on the dense stereo correspondence problem and further multi-view stereo techniques.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] At the same time, variations of graph cut were used to solve image segmentation.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] This decade also marked the first time statistical learning techniques were used in practice to recognize faces in images (see Eigenface).
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Toward the end of the 1990s, a significant change came about with the increased interaction between the fields of computer graphics and computer vision.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] This included image-based rendering, image morphing, view interpolation, panoramic image stitching and early light-field rendering.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Recent work has seen the resurgence of feature-based methods used in conjunction with machine learning techniques and complex optimization frameworks.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The advancement of Deep Learning techniques has brought further life to the field of computer vision.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The accuracy of deep learning algorithms on several benchmark computer vision data sets for tasks ranging from classification, segmentation and optical flow has surpassed prior methods.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Solid-state physics is another field that is closely related to computer vision.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems rely on image sensors, which detect electromagnetic radiation, which is typically in the form of either visible, infrared or ultraviolet light.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The sensors are designed using quantum physics.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The process by which light interacts with surfaces is explained using physics.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Physics explains the behavior of optics which are a core part of most imaging systems.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Sophisticated image sensors even require quantum mechanics to provide a complete understanding of the image formation process.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Also, various measurement problems in physics can be addressed using computer vision, for example, motion in fluids.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring-textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Neurobiology has greatly influenced the development of computer vision algorithms.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Over the last century, there has been an extensive study of eyes, neurons, and brain structures devoted to the processing of visual stimuli in both humans and various animals.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] This has led to a coarse yet convoluted description of how natural vision systems operate in order to solve certain vision-related tasks.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] These results have led to a sub-field within computer vision where artificial systems are designed to mimic the processing and behavior of biological systems at different levels of complexity.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Also, some of the learning-based methods developed within computer vision (*e.g.* neural net and deep learning based image and feature analysis and classification) have their background in neurobiology.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The Neocognitron, a neural network developed in the 1970s by Kunihiko Fukushima, is an early example of computer vision taking direct inspiration from neurobiology, specifically the primary visual cortex.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Some strands of computer vision research are closely related to the study of biological vision—indeed, just as many strands of AI research are closely tied with research into human intelligence and the use of stored knowledge to interpret, integrate, and utilize visual information.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The field of biological vision studies and models the physiological processes behind visual perception in humans and other animals.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Computer vision, on the other hand, develops and describes the algorithms implemented in software and hardware behind artificial vision systems.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] An interdisciplinary exchange between biological and computer vision has proven fruitful for both fields.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Yet another field related to computer vision is signal processing.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Many methods for processing one-variable signals, typically temporal signals, can be extended in a natural way to the processing of two-variable signals or multi-variable signals in computer vision.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] However, because of the specific nature of images, there are many methods developed within computer vision that have no counterpart in the processing of one-variable signals.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Together with the multi-dimensionality of the signal, this defines a subfield in signal processing as a part of computer vision.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Robot navigation sometimes deals with autonomous path planning or deliberation for robotic systems to navigate through an environment.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] A detailed understanding of these environments is required to navigate through them.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Visual computing is a generic term for all computer science disciplines dealing with images and 3D models, such as computer graphics, image processing, visualization, computer vision, virtual and augmented reality, video processing, and computational visualistics.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes aspects of pattern recognition, human computer interaction, machine learning and digital libraries.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The core challenges are the acquisition, processing, analysis and rendering of visual information (mainly images and video).
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Application areas include industrial quality control, medical image processing and visualization, surveying, robotics, multimedia systems, virtual heritage, special effects in movies and television, and ludology.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes digital art and digital media studies.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Besides the above-mentioned views on computer vision, many of the related research topics can also be studied from a purely mathematical point of view.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] For example, many methods in computer vision are based on statistics, optimization or geometry.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Finally, a significant part of the field is devoted to the implementation aspect of computer vision; how existing methods can be realized in various combinations of software and hardware, or how these methods can be modified in order to gain processing speed without losing too much performance.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Computer vision is also used in fashion eCommerce, inventory management, patent search, furniture, and the beauty industry.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The fields most closely related to computer vision are image processing, image analysis and machine vision.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] There is a significant overlap in the range of techniques and applications that these cover.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] This implies that the basic techniques that are used and developed in these fields are similar, something which can be interpreted as there is only one field with different names.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] In image processing, the input and output are both images, whereas in computer vision, the input is an image or video, and the output could be an enhanced image, an analysis of the image's content, or even a system's behavior based on that analysis.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Computer graphics produces image data from 3D models, and computer vision often produces 3D models from image data.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] There is also a trend towards a combination of the two disciplines, *e.g.*, as explored in augmented reality.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Photogrammetry also overlaps with computer vision, e.g., stereophotogrammetry vs. computer stereo vision.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Applications range from tasks such as industrial machine vision systems which, say, inspect bottles speeding by on a production line, to research into artificial intelligence and computers or robots that can comprehend the world around them.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The computer vision and machine vision fields have significant overlap.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Computer vision covers the core technology of automated image analysis which is used in many fields.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Machine vision usually refers to a process of combining automated image analysis with other methods and technologies to provide automated inspection and robot guidance in industrial applications.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] In many computer-vision applications, computers are pre-programmed to solve a particular task, but methods based on learning are now becoming increasingly common.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] For 2024, the leading areas of computer vision were industry (market size US$5.22 billion), medicine (market size US$2.6 billion), military (market size US$996.2 million).
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] One of the most prominent application fields is medical computer vision, or medical image processing, characterized by the extraction of information from image data to diagnose a patient.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] An example of this is the detection of tumours, arteriosclerosis or other malign changes, and a variety of dental pathologies; measurements of organ dimensions, blood flow, etc. are another example.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] It also supports medical research by providing new information: *e.g.*, about the structure of the brain or the quality of medical treatments.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Applications of computer vision in the medical area also include enhancement of images interpreted by humans—ultrasonic images or X-ray images, for example—to reduce the influence of noise.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] A second application area in computer vision is in industry, sometimes called machine vision, where information is extracted for the purpose of supporting a production process.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] One example is quality control where details or final products are being automatically inspected in order to find defects.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] One of the most prevalent fields for such inspecti is the Wafer industry in which every single Wafer is being measured and inspected for inaccuracies or defects to prevent a computer chip from coming to market in an unusable manner.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Another example is a measurement of the position and orientation of details to be picked up by a robot arm.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Machine vision is also heavily used in the agricultural processes to remove undesirable foodstuff from bulk material, a process called optical sorting.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The obvious examples are the detection of enemy soldiers or vehicles and missile guidance.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] More advanced systems for missile guidance send the missile to an area rather than a specific target, and target selection is made when the missile reaches the area based on locally acquired image data.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Modern military concepts, such as "battlefield awareness", imply that various sensors, including image sensors, provide a rich set of information about a combat scene that can be used to support strategic decisions.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] In this case, automatic processing of the data is used to reduce complexity and to fuse information from multiple sensors to increase reliability.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] One of the newer application areas is autonomous vehicles, which include submersibles, land-based vehicles (small robots with wheels, cars, or trucks), aerial vehicles, and unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV).
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The level of autonomy ranges from fully autonomous (unmanned) vehicles to vehicles where computer-vision-based systems support a driver or a pilot in various situations.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Fully autonomous vehicles typically use computer vision for navigation, e.g., for knowing where they are or mapping their environment (SLAM), for detecting obstacles.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] It can also be used for detecting certain task-specific events, *e.g.*, a UAV looking for forest fires.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Examples of supporting systems are obstacle warning systems in cars, cameras and LiDAR sensors in vehicles, and systems for autonomous landing of aircraft.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Several car manufacturers have demonstrated systems for autonomous driving of cars.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] There are ample examples of military autonomous vehicles ranging from advanced missiles to UAVs for recon missions or missile guidance.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Space exploration is already being made with autonomous vehicles using computer vision, *e.g.*, NASA's *Curiosity* and CNSA's *Yutu-2* rover.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Materials such as rubber and silicon are being used to create sensors that allow for applications such as detecting microundulations and calibrating robotic hands.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Rubber can be used in order to create a mold that can be placed over a finger, inside of this mold would be multiple strain gauges.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The finger mold and sensors could then be placed on top of a small sheet of rubber containing an array of rubber pins.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] A user can then wear the finger mold and trace a surface.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] A computer can then read the data from the strain gauges and measure if one or more of the pins are being pushed upward.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] If a pin is being pushed upward then the computer can recognize this as an imperfection in the surface.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] This sort of technology is useful in order to receive accurate data on imperfections on a very large surface.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Another variation of this finger mold sensor are sensors that contain a camera suspended in silicon.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The silicon forms a dome around the outside of the camera and embedded in the silicon are point markers that are equally spaced.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] These cameras can then be placed on devices such as robotic hands in order to allow the computer to receive highly accurate tactile data.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Each of the application areas described above employ a range of computer vision tasks; more or less well-defined measurement problems or processing problems, which can be solved using a variety of methods.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Some examples of typical computer vision tasks are presented below.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Computer vision tasks include methods for acquiring, processing, analyzing and understanding digital images, and extraction of high-dimensional data from the real world in order to produce numerical or symbolic information, *e.g.*, in the forms of decisions.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Understanding in this context means the transformation of visual images into descriptions of the world that can interface with other thought processes and elicit appropriate action.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] This image understanding can be seen as the disentangling of symbolic information from image data using models constructed with the aid of geometry, physics, statistics, and learning theory.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The classical problem in computer vision, image processing, and machine vision is that of determining whether or not the image data contains some specific object, feature, or activity.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Different varieties of recognition problem are described in the literature.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Currently, the best algorithms for such tasks are based on convolutional neural networks.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] An illustration of their capabilities is given by the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge; this is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and 1000 object classes used in the competition.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests is now close to that of humans.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on the stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters (an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras).
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained classes, such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this with ease.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Several tasks relate to motion estimation, where an image sequence is processed to produce an estimate of the velocity either at each points in the image or in the 3D scene or even of the camera that produces the images.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Given one or (typically) more images of a scene, or a video, scene reconstruction aims at computing a 3D model of the scene.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] In the simplest case, the model can be a set of 3D points.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods produce a complete 3D surface model.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The advent of 3D imaging not requiring motion or scanning, and related processing algorithms is enabling rapid advances in this field.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Grid-based 3D sensing can be used to acquire 3D images from multiple angles.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Algorithms are now available to stitch multiple 3D images together into point clouds and 3D models.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Image restoration comes into the picture when the original image is degraded or damaged due to some external factors like lens wrong positioning, transmission interference, low lighting or motion blurs, etc., which is referred to as noise.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] When the images are degraded or damaged, the information to be extracted from them also gets damaged.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Therefore, we need to recover or restore the image as it was intended to be.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The aim of image restoration is the removal of noise (sensor noise, motion blur, etc.) from images.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The simplest possible approach for noise removal is various types of filters, such as low-pass filters or median filters.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods assume a model of how the local image structures look to distinguish them from noise.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] By first analyzing the image data in terms of the local image structures, such as lines or edges, and then controlling the filtering based on local information from the analysis step, a better level of noise removal is usually obtained compared to the simpler approaches.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The organization of a computer vision system is highly application-dependent.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Some systems are stand-alone applications that solve a specific measurement or detection problem, while others constitute a sub-system of a larger design which, for example, also contains sub-systems for control of mechanical actuators, planning, information databases, man-machine interfaces, etc.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The specific implementation of a computer vision system also depends on whether its functionality is pre-specified or if some part of it can be learned or modified during operation.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Many functions are unique to the application.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] There are, however, typical functions that are found in many computer vision systems.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] More complex features may be related to texture, shape, or motion.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Image-understanding systems (IUS) include three levels of abstraction as follows: low level includes image primitives such as edges, texture elements, or regions; intermediate level includes boundaries, surfaces and volumes; and high level includes objects, scenes, or events.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Many of these requirements are entirely topics for further research.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] The representational requirements in the designing of IUS for these levels are: representation of prototypical concepts, concept organization, spatial knowledge, temporal knowledge, scaling, and description by comparison and differentiation.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] While inference refers to the process of deriving new, not explicitly represented facts from currently known facts, control refers to the process that selects which of the many inference, search, and matching techniques should be applied at a particular stage of processing.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Inference and control requirements for IUS are: search and hypothesis activation, matching and hypothesis testing, generation and use of expectations, change and focus of attention, certainty and strength of belief, inference and goal satisfaction.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] There are many kinds of computer vision systems; however, all of them contain these basic elements: a power source, at least one image acquisition device (camera, ccd, etc.), a processor, and control and communication cables or some kind of wireless interconnection mechanism.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] In addition, a practical vision system contains software, as well as a display in order to monitor the system.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Vision systems for inner spaces, as most industrial ones, contain an illumination system and may be placed in a controlled environment.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Furthermore, a completed system includes many accessories, such as camera supports, cables, and connectors.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems use visible-light cameras passively viewing a scene at frame rates of at most 60 frames per second (usually far slower).
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Such hardware captures "images" that are then processed often using the same computer vision algorithms used to process visible-light images.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] For applications in robotics, fast, real-time video systems are critically important and often can simplify the processing needed for certain algorithms.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] When combined with a high-speed projector, fast image acquisition allows 3D measurement and feature tracking to be realized.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] Egocentric vision systems are composed of a wearable camera that automatically take pictures from a first-person perspective.
[src:image-captioning/computer-vision] As of 2016, vision processing units are emerging as a new class of processors to complement CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs) in this role.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A **convolutional neural network** (**CNN**) is a type of feedforward neural network that learns features via filter (or kernel) optimization.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This type of deep learning network has been applied to process and make predictions from many different types of data including text, images and audio.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are the de-facto standard in deep learning-based approaches to computer vision and image processing, and have only recently been replaced—in some cases—by newer architectures such as the transformer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Vanishing gradients and exploding gradients, seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks, are prevented by the regularization that comes from using shared weights over fewer connections.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, for *each* neuron in the fully-connected layer, 10,000 weights would be required for processing an image sized 100 × 100 pixels.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, applying cascaded *convolution* (or cross-correlation) kernels, only 25 weights for each convolutional layer are required to process 5x5-sized tiles.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Higher-layer features are extracted from wider context windows, compared to lower-layer features.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are also known as **shift invariant** or **space invariant artificial neural networks**, based on the shared-weight architecture of the convolution kernels or filters that slide along input features and provide translation-equivariant responses known as feature maps.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Counter-intuitively, most convolutional neural networks are not invariant to translation, due to the downsampling operation they apply to the input.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Feedforward neural networks are usually fully connected networks, that is, each neuron in one layer is connected to all neurons in the next layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "full connectivity" of these networks makes them prone to overfitting data.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks were inspired by biological processes in that the connectivity pattern between neurons resembles the organization of the animal visual cortex.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Individual cortical neurons respond to stimuli only in a restricted region of the visual field known as the receptive field.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The receptive fields of different neurons partially overlap such that they cover the entire visual field.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use relatively little pre-processing compared to other image classification algorithms.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This means that the network learns to optimize the filters (or kernels) through automated learning, whereas in traditional algorithms these filters are hand-engineered.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This simplifies and automates the process, enhancing efficiency and scalability overcoming human-intervention bottlenecks.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A convolutional neural network consists of an input layer, hidden layers and an output layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional neural network, the hidden layers include one or more layers that perform convolutions.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typically this includes a layer that performs a dot product of the convolution kernel with the layer's input matrix.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This product is usually the Frobenius inner product, and its activation function is commonly ReLU.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As the convolution kernel slides along the input matrix for the layer, the convolution operation generates a feature map, which in turn contributes to the input of the next layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is followed by other layers such as pooling layers, fully connected layers, and normalization layers.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Here it should be noted how close a convolutional neural network is to a matched filter.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (number of inputs) × (feature map height) × (feature map width) × (feature map channels).
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional layers convolve the input and pass its result to the next layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to the response of a neuron in the visual cortex to a specific stimulus.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each convolutional neuron processes data only for its receptive field.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although fully connected feedforward neural networks can be used to learn features and classify data, this architecture is generally impractical for larger inputs (e.g., high-resolution images), which would require massive numbers of neurons because each pixel is a relevant input feature.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A fully connected layer for an image of size 100 × 100 has 10,000 weights for *each* neuron in the second layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution reduces the number of free parameters, allowing the network to be deeper.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, using a 5 × 5 tiling region, each with the same shared weights, requires only 25 neurons.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using shared weights means there are many fewer parameters, which helps avoid the vanishing gradients and exploding gradients problems seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To speed processing, standard convolutional layers can be replaced by depthwise separable convolutional layers, which are based on a depthwise convolution followed by a pointwise convolution.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The *depthwise convolution* is a spatial convolution applied independently over each channel of the input tensor, while the *pointwise convolution* is a standard convolution restricted to the use of $1\times 1$ kernels.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks may include local and/or global pooling layers along with traditional convolutional layers.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling layers reduce the dimensions of data by combining the outputs of neuron clusters at one layer into a single neuron in the next layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Local pooling combines small clusters, tiling sizes such as 2 × 2 are commonly used.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Global pooling acts on all the neurons of the feature map.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are two common types of pooling in popular use: max and average.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] *Max pooling* uses the maximum value of each local cluster of neurons in the feature map, while *average pooling* takes the average value.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fully connected layers connect every neuron in one layer to every neuron in another layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the same as a traditional multilayer perceptron neural network (MLP).
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in the fully connected layer receives input from all the neurons in the previous layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These inputs are weighted and summed with the corresponding biases, and then passed through an activation function to perform a nonlinear transformation, generating the output.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The flattened matrix goes through a fully connected layer to classify the images.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In neural networks, each neuron receives input from some number of locations in the previous layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional layer, each neuron receives input from only a restricted area of the previous layer called the neuron's *receptive field*.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Whereas, in a fully connected layer, the receptive field is the *entire previous layer*.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, in each convolutional layer, each neuron takes input from a larger area in the input than previous layers.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is due to applying the convolution over and over, which takes the value of a pixel into account, as well as its surrounding pixels.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When using dilated layers, the number of pixels in the receptive field remains constant, but the field is more sparsely populated as its dimensions grow when combining the effect of several layers.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To manipulate the receptive field size as desired, there are some alternatives to the standard convolutional layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, atrous or dilated convolution expands the receptive field size without increasing the number of parameters by interleaving visible and blind regions.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Moreover, a single dilated convolutional layer can comprise filters with multiple dilation ratios, thus having a variable receptive field size.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in a neural network computes an output value by applying a specific function to the input values received from the receptive field in the previous layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The function that is applied to the input values is determined by a vector of weights and a bias (typically real numbers).
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning consists of iteratively adjusting these biases and weights.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The vectors of weights and biases are called *filters* and represent particular features of the input (e.g., a particular shape).
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A distinguishing feature of CNNs is that many neurons can share the same filter.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces the memory footprint because a single bias and a single vector of weights are used across all receptive fields that share that filter, as opposed to each receptive field having its own bias and vector weighting.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional neural network is essentially the reverse of a CNN.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It consists of deconvolutional layers and unpooling layers.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional layer is the transpose of a convolutional layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Specifically, a convolutional layer can be written as a multiplication with a matrix, and a deconvolutional layer is multiplication with the transpose of that matrix.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The max-unpooling layer is the simplest, as it simply copies each entry multiple times.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a 2-by-2 max-unpooling layer is $[x]\mapsto {\begin{bmatrix}x&x\\x&x\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Deconvolution layers are used in image generators.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By default, it creates periodic checkerboard artifact, which can be fixed by upscale-then-convolve.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNN are often compared to the way the brain achieves vision processing in living organisms.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Work by Hubel and Wiesel in the 1950s and 1960s showed that cat visual cortices contain neurons that individually respond to small regions of the visual field.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Provided the eyes are not moving, the region of visual space within which visual stimuli affect the firing of a single neuron is known as its receptive field.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neighboring cells have similar and overlapping receptive fields.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Receptive field size and location varies systematically across the cortex to form a complete map of visual space.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The cortex in each hemisphere represents the contralateral visual field.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hubel and Wiesel also proposed a cascading model of these two types of cells for use in pattern recognition tasks.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same paper, Fukushima also introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "neocognitron" was introduced by Fukushima in 1980.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Several supervised and unsupervised learning algorithms have been proposed over the decades to train the weights of a neocognitron.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Today, however, the CNN architecture is usually trained through backpropagation.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's ReLU activation function was not used in his neocognitron since all the weights were nonnegative; lateral inhibition was used instead.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The rectifier has become a very popular activation function for CNNs and deep neural networks in general.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The term "convolution" first appears in neural networks in a paper by Toshiteru Homma, Les Atlas, and Robert Marks II at the first Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems in 1987.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their paper replaced multiplication with convolution in time, inherently providing shift invariance, motivated by and connecting more directly to the signal-processing concept of a filter, and demonstrated it on a speech recognition task.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They also pointed out that as a data-trainable system, convolution is essentially equivalent to correlation since reversal of the weights does not affect the final learned function ("For convenience, we denote * as correlation instead of convolution.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that convolving a(t) with b(t) is equivalent to correlating a(-t) with b(t).").
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Modern CNN implementations typically do correlation and call it convolution, for convenience, as they did here.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel et al. for phoneme recognition and was an early convolutional network exhibiting shift-invariance.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A TDNN is a 1-D convolutional neural net where the convolution is performed along the time axis of the data.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the first CNN utilizing weight sharing in combination with a training by gradient descent, using backpropagation.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, while also using a pyramidal structure as in the neocognitron, it performed a global optimization of the weights instead of a local one.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs are convolutional networks that share weights along the temporal dimension.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They allow speech signals to be processed time-invariantly.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Hampshire and Waibel introduced a variant that performs a two-dimensional convolution.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since these TDNNs operated on spectrograms, the resulting phoneme recognition system was invariant to both time and frequency shifts, as with images processed by a neocognitron.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs improved the performance of far-distance speech recognition.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) designed a 2-D CNN system to recognize hand-written ZIP Code numbers.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the lack of an efficient training method to determine the kernel coefficients of the involved convolutions meant that all the coefficients had to be laboriously hand-designed.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Following the advances in the training of 1-D CNNs by Waibel et al.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) used back-propagation to learn the convolution kernel coefficients directly from images of hand-written numbers.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning was thus fully automatic, performed better than manual coefficient design, and was suited to a broader range of image recognition problems and image types.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1988) used back-propagation to train the convolution kernels of a CNN for alphabets recognition.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was called shift-invariant pattern recognition neural network before the name CNN was coined later in the early 1990s.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Wei Zhang et al. also applied the same CNN without the last fully connected layer for medical image object segmentation (1991) and breast cancer detection in mammograms (1994).
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach became a foundation of modern computer vision.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Yamaguchi et al. introduced the concept of max pooling, a fixed filtering operation that calculates and propagates the maximum value of a given region.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They did so by combining TDNNs with max pooling to realize a speaker-independent isolated word recognition system.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In their system they used several TDNNs per word, one for each syllable.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The results of each TDNN over the input signal were combined using max pooling and the outputs of the pooling layers were then passed on to networks performing the actual word classification.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a variant of the neocognitron called the *cresceptron*, instead of using Fukushima's spatial averaging with inhibition and saturation, J.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weng et al. in 1993 used max pooling, where a downsampling unit computes the maximum of the activations of the units in its patch, introducing this method into the vision field.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is often used in modern CNNs.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5, a pioneering 7-level convolutional network by LeCun et al. in 1995, classifies hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The ability to process higher-resolution images requires larger and more layers of convolutional neural networks, so this technique is constrained by the availability of computing resources.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was superior than other commercial courtesy amount reading systems (as of 1995).
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The system was integrated in NCR's check reading systems, and fielded in several American banks since June 1996, reading millions of checks per day.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A shift-invariant neural network was proposed by Wei Zhang et al. for image character recognition in 1988.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is a modified Neocognitron by keeping only the convolutional interconnections between the image feature layers and the last fully connected layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was trained with back-propagation.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The training algorithm was further improved in 1991 to improve its generalization ability.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model architecture was modified by removing the last fully connected layer and applied for medical image segmentation (1991) and automatic detection of breast cancer in mammograms (1994).
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A different convolution-based design was proposed in 1988 for application to decomposition of one-dimensional electromyography convolved signals via de-convolution.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This design was modified in 1989 to other de-convolution-based designs.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although CNNs were invented in the 1980s, their breakthrough in the 2000s required fast implementations on graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Jung that standard neural networks can be greatly accelerated on GPUs.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 20 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2005, another paper also emphasised the value of GPGPU for machine learning.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The first GPU-implementation of a CNN was described in 2006 by K.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 4 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same period, GPUs were also used for unsupervised training of deep belief networks.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2010, Dan Ciresan et al. at IDSIA trained deep feedforward networks on GPUs.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, they extended this to CNNs, accelerating by 60 compared to training CPU.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, the network won an image recognition contest where they achieved superhuman performance for the first time.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Then they won more competitions and achieved state of the art on several benchmarks.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Subsequently, AlexNet, a similar GPU-based CNN by Alex Krizhevsky et al. won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was an early catalytic event for the AI boom.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Compared to the training of CNNs using GPUs, not much attention was given to CPU.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (Viebke et al 2019) parallelizes CNN by thread- and SIMD-level parallelism that is available on the Intel Xeon Phi.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the past, traditional multilayer perceptron (MLP) models were used for image recognition.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the full connectivity between nodes caused the curse of dimensionality, and was computationally intractable with higher-resolution images.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A 1000×1000-pixel image with RGB color channels has 3 million weights per fully-connected neuron, which is too high to feasibly process efficiently at scale.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, in CIFAR-10, images are only of size 32×32×3 (32 wide, 32 high, 3 color channels), so a single fully connected neuron in the first hidden layer of a regular neural network would have 32*32*3 = 3,072 weights.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Also, such network architecture does not take into account the spatial structure of data, treating input pixels which are far apart in the same way as pixels that are close together.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This ignores locality of reference in data with a grid-topology (such as images), both computationally and semantically.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, full connectivity of neurons is wasteful for purposes such as image recognition that are dominated by spatially local input patterns.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional neural networks are variants of multilayer perceptrons, designed to emulate the behavior of a visual cortex.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These models mitigate the challenges posed by the MLP architecture by exploiting the strong spatially local correlation present in natural images.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Together, these properties allow CNNs to achieve better generalization on vision problems.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weight sharing dramatically reduces the number of free parameters learned, thus lowering the memory requirements for running the network and allowing the training of larger, more powerful networks.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A CNN architecture is formed by a stack of distinct layers that transform the input volume into an output volume (e.g. holding the class scores) through a differentiable function.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A few distinct types of layers are commonly used.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The convolutional layer is the core building block of a CNN.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The layer's parameters consist of a set of learnable filters (or kernels), which have a small receptive field, but extend through the full depth of the input volume.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] During the forward pass, each filter is convolved across the width and height of the input volume, computing the dot product between the filter entries and the input, producing a 2-dimensional activation map of that filter.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As a result, the network learns filters that activate when it detects some specific type of feature at some spatial position in the input.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Stacking the activation maps for all filters along the depth dimension forms the full output volume of the convolution layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Every entry in the output volume can thus also be interpreted as an output of a neuron that looks at a small region in the input.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each entry in an activation map use the same set of parameters that define the filter.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has been adapted for use in convolutional layers by using sparse patches with a high-mask ratio and a global response normalization layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When dealing with high-dimensional inputs such as images, it is impractical to connect neurons to all neurons in the previous volume because such a network architecture does not take the spatial structure of the data into account.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks exploit spatially local correlation by enforcing a sparse local connectivity pattern between neurons of adjacent layers: each neuron is connected to only a small region of the input volume.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The extent of this connectivity is a hyperparameter called the receptive field of the neuron.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The connections are local in space (along width and height), but always extend along the entire depth of the input volume.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Such an architecture ensures that the learned filters produce the strongest response to a spatially local input pattern.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The spatial size of the output volume is a function of the input volume size W , the kernel field size K of the convolutional layer neurons, the stride S , and the amount of zero padding P on the border.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] If this number is not an integer, then the strides are incorrect and the neurons cannot be tiled to fit across the input volume in a symmetric way.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In general, setting zero padding to be ${\textstyle P=(K-1)/2}$ when the stride is $S=1$ ensures that the input volume and output volume will have the same size spatially.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, it is not always completely necessary to use all of the neurons of the previous layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a neural network designer may decide to use just a portion of padding.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A parameter sharing scheme is used in convolutional layers to control the number of free parameters.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It relies on the assumption that if a patch feature is useful to compute at some spatial position, then it should also be useful to compute at other positions.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Denoting a single 2-dimensional slice of depth as a *depth slice*, the neurons in each depth slice are constrained to use the same weights and bias.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since all neurons in a single depth slice share the same parameters, the forward pass in each depth slice of the convolutional layer can be computed as a convolution of the neuron's weights with the input volume.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Therefore, it is common to refer to the sets of weights as a filter (or a kernel), which is convolved with the input.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The result of this convolution is an activation map, and the set of activation maps for each different filter are stacked together along the depth dimension to produce the output volume.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Parameter sharing contributes to the translation invariance of the CNN architecture.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sometimes, the parameter sharing assumption may not make sense.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is especially the case when the input images to a CNN have some specific centered structure; for which we expect completely different features to be learned on different spatial locations.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One practical example is when the inputs are faces that have been centered in the image: we might expect different eye-specific or hair-specific features to be learned in different parts of the image.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In that case it is common to relax the parameter sharing scheme, and instead simply call the layer a "locally connected layer".
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In this layer, the convolutional kernels' parameters are not shared.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network learns independent weights and biases for each spatial location.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This allows each location to have its own feature-learning ability, making it better suited to handle images with distinct central structures or irregular features.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another important concept of CNNs is pooling, which is used as a form of non-linear down-sampling.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling provides downsampling because it reduces the spatial dimensions (height and width) of the input feature maps while retaining the most important information.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are several non-linear functions to implement pooling, where *max pooling* and *average pooling* are the most common.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling aggregates information from small regions of the input creating partitions of the input feature map, typically using a fixed-size window (like 2x2) and applying a stride (often 2) to move the window across the input.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that without using a stride greater than 1, pooling would not perform downsampling, as it would simply move the pooling window across the input one step at a time, without reducing the size of the feature map.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the stride is what actually causes the downsampling by determining how much the pooling window moves over the input.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Intuitively, the exact location of a feature is less important than its rough location relative to other features.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the idea behind the use of pooling in convolutional neural networks.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer serves to progressively reduce the spatial size of the representation, to reduce the number of parameters, memory footprint and amount of computation in the network, and hence to also control overfitting.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is common to periodically insert a pooling layer between successive convolutional layers (each one typically followed by an activation function, such as a ReLU layer) in a CNN architecture.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] While pooling layers contribute to local translation invariance, they do not provide global translation invariance in a CNN, unless a form of global pooling is used.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer commonly operates independently on every depth, or slice, of the input and resizes it spatially.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The depth dimension remains unchanged (this is true for other forms of pooling as well).
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In addition to max pooling, pooling units can use other functions, such as average pooling or ℓ2-norm pooling.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Average pooling was often used historically but has recently fallen out of favor compared to max pooling, which generally performs better in practice.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to the effects of fast spatial reduction of the size of the representation, there is a recent trend towards using smaller filters or discarding pooling layers altogether.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A channel max pooling (CMP) operation layer conducts the MP operation along the channel side among the corresponding positions of the consecutive feature maps for the purpose of redundant information elimination.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The CMP makes the significant features gather together within fewer channels, which is important for fine-grained image classification that needs more discriminating features.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Meanwhile, another advantage of the CMP operation is to make the channel number of feature maps smaller before it connects to the first fully connected (FC) layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Similar to the MP operation, we denote the input feature maps and output feature maps of a CMP layer as F ∈ R(C×M×N) and C ∈ R(c×M×N), respectively, where C and c are the channel numbers of the input and output feature maps, M and N are the widths and the height of the feature maps, respectively.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that the CMP operation only changes the channel number of the feature maps.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The width and the height of the feature maps are not changed, which is different from the MP operation.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is the abbreviation of rectified linear unit.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was proposed by Alston Householder in 1941, and used in CNN by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1969.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU applies the non-saturating activation function ${\textstyle f(x)=\max(0,x)}$ .
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It effectively removes negative values from an activation map by setting them to zero.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It introduces nonlinearity to the decision function and in the overall network without affecting the receptive fields of the convolution layers.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, Xavier Glorot, Antoine Bordes and Yoshua Bengio found that ReLU enables better training of deeper networks, compared to widely used activation functions prior to 2011.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other functions can also be used to increase nonlinearity, for example the saturating hyperbolic tangent $f(x)=\tanh(x)$ , $f(x)=|\tanh(x)|$ , and the sigmoid function ${\textstyle \sigma (x)=(1+e^{-x})^{-1}}$ .
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is often preferred to other functions because it trains the neural network several times faster without a significant penalty to generalization accuracy.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] After several convolutional and max pooling layers, the final classification is done via fully connected layers.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neurons in a fully connected layer have connections to all activations in the previous layer, as seen in regular (non-convolutional) artificial neural networks.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their activations can thus be computed as an affine transformation, with matrix multiplication followed by a bias offset (vector addition of a learned or fixed bias term).
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "loss layer", or "loss function", exemplifies how training penalizes the deviation between the predicted output of the network, and the true data labels (during supervised learning).
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Various loss functions can be used, depending on the specific task.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The Softmax loss function is used for predicting a single class of *K* mutually exclusive classes.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sigmoid cross-entropy loss is used for predicting *K* independent probability values in $[0,1]$ .
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Euclidean loss is used for regressing to real-valued labels $(-\infty ,\infty )$ .
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are various settings that are used to control the learning process.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use more hyperparameters than a standard multilayer perceptron (MLP).
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Padding is the addition of (typically) 0-valued pixels on the borders of an image.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is done so that the border pixels are not undervalued (lost) from the output because they would ordinarily participate in only a single receptive field instance.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The padding applied is typically one less than the corresponding kernel dimension.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a convolutional layer using 3x3 kernels would receive a 2-pixel pad, that is 1 pixel on each side of the image.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The stride is the number of pixels that the analysis window moves on each iteration.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A stride of 2 means that each kernel is offset by 2 pixels from its predecessor.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since feature map size decreases with depth, layers near the input layer tend to have fewer filters while higher layers can have more.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To equalize computation at each layer, the product of feature values *va* with pixel position is kept roughly constant across layers.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Preserving more information about the input would require keeping the total number of activations (number of feature maps times number of pixel positions) non-decreasing from one layer to the next.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The number of feature maps directly controls the capacity and depends on the number of available examples and task complexity.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Common filter sizes found in the literature vary greatly, and are usually chosen based on the data set.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typical filter sizes range from 1x1 to 7x7.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As two famous examples, AlexNet used 3x3, 5x5, and 11x11.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The challenge is to find the right level of granularity so as to create abstractions at the proper scale, given a particular data set, and without overfitting.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is typically used, often with a 2x2 dimension.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This implies that the input is drastically downsampled, reducing processing cost.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Greater pooling reduces the dimension of the signal, and may result in unacceptable information loss.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Often, non-overlapping pooling windows perform best.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Dilation involves ignoring pixels within a kernel.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces processing memory potentially without significant signal loss.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A dilation of 2 on a 3x3 kernel expands the kernel to 5x5, while still processing 9 (evenly spaced) pixels.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Accordingly, dilation of 4 expands the kernel to 7x7.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is commonly assumed that CNNs are invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution or pooling layers within a CNN that do not have a stride greater than one are indeed equivariant to translations of the input.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Furthermore, if a CNN makes use of fully connected layers, translation equivariance does not imply translation invariance, as the fully connected layers are not invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One solution for complete translation invariance is avoiding any down-sampling throughout the network and applying global average pooling at the last layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Additionally, several other partial solutions have been proposed, such as anti-aliasing before downsampling operations, spatial transformer networks, data augmentation, subsampling combined with pooling, and capsule neural networks.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The accuracy of the final model is typically estimated on a sub-part of the dataset set apart at the start, often called a test set.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, methods such as *k*-fold cross-validation are applied.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other strategies include using conformal prediction.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Regularization is a process of introducing additional information to solve an ill-posed problem or to prevent overfitting.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use various types of regularization.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because networks have so many parameters, they are prone to overfitting.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One method to reduce overfitting is dropout, introduced in 2014.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At each training stage, individual nodes are either "dropped out" of the net (ignored) with probability $1-p$ or kept with probability p , so that a reduced network is left; incoming and outgoing edges to a dropped-out node are also removed.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Only the reduced network is trained on the data in that stage.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The removed nodes are then reinserted into the network with their original weights.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the training stages, p is usually 0.5; for input nodes, it is typically much higher because information is directly lost when input nodes are ignored.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At testing time after training has finished, we would ideally like to find a sample average of all possible $2^{n}$ dropped-out networks; unfortunately this is unfeasible for large values of n .
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, we can find an approximation by using the full network with each node's output weighted by a factor of p , so the expected value of the output of any node is the same as in the training stages.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the biggest contribution of the dropout method: although it effectively generates $2^{n}$ neural nets, and as such allows for model combination, at test time only a single network needs to be tested.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By avoiding training all nodes on all training data, dropout decreases overfitting.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The method also significantly improves training speed.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This makes the model combination practical, even for deep neural networks.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The technique seems to reduce node interactions, leading them to learn more robust features that better generalize to new data.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is the generalization of dropout in which each connection, rather than each output unit, can be dropped with probability $1-p$ .
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each unit thus receives input from a random subset of units in the previous layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is similar to dropout as it introduces dynamic sparsity within the model, but differs in that the sparsity is on the weights, rather than the output vectors of a layer.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the fully connected layer with DropConnect becomes a sparsely connected layer in which the connections are chosen at random during the training stage.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A major drawback to dropout is that it does not have the same benefits for convolutional layers, where the neurons are not fully connected.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach is free of hyperparameters and can be combined with other regularization approaches, such as dropout and data augmentation.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] An alternate view of stochastic pooling is that it is equivalent to standard max pooling but with many copies of an input image, each having small local deformations.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to explicit elastic deformations of the input images, which delivers excellent performance on the MNIST data set.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using stochastic pooling in a multilayer model gives an exponential number of deformations since the selections in higher layers are independent of those below.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because the degree of model overfitting is determined by both its power and the amount of training it receives, providing a convolutional network with more training examples can reduce overfitting.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because there is often not enough available data to train, especially considering that some part should be spared for later testing, two approaches are to either generate new data from scratch (if possible) or perturb existing data to create new ones.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, input images can be cropped, rotated, or rescaled to create new examples with the same labels as the original training set.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One of the simplest methods to prevent overfitting of a network is to simply stop the training before overfitting has had a chance to occur.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It comes with the disadvantage that the learning process is halted.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another simple way to prevent overfitting is to limit the number of parameters, typically by limiting the number of hidden units in each layer or limiting network depth.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For convolutional networks, the filter size also affects the number of parameters.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Limiting the number of parameters restricts the predictive power of the network directly, reducing the complexity of the function that it can perform on the data, and thus limits the amount of overfitting.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A simple form of added regularizer is weight decay, which simply adds an additional error, proportional to the sum of weights (L1 norm) or squared magnitude (L2 norm) of the weight vector, to the error at each node.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The level of acceptable model complexity can be reduced by increasing the proportionality constant('alpha' hyperparameter), thus increasing the penalty for large weight vectors.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L2 regularization is the most common form of regularization.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It can be implemented by penalizing the squared magnitude of all parameters directly in the objective.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The L2 regularization has the intuitive interpretation of heavily penalizing peaky weight vectors and preferring diffuse weight vectors.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to multiplicative interactions between weights and inputs this has the useful property of encouraging the network to use all of its inputs a little rather than some of its inputs a lot.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It makes the weight vectors sparse during optimization.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, neurons with L1 regularization end up using only a sparse subset of their most important inputs and become nearly invariant to the noisy inputs.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L1 with L2 regularization can be combined; this is called elastic net regularization.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another form of regularization is to enforce an absolute upper bound on the magnitude of the weight vector for every neuron and use projected gradient descent to enforce the constraint.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In practice, this corresponds to performing the parameter update as normal, and then enforcing the constraint by clamping the weight vector ${\vec {w}}$ of every neuron to satisfy $\|{\vec {w}}\|_{2}<c$ .
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Some papers report improvements when using this form of regularization.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Pooling loses the precise spatial relationships between high-level parts (such as nose and mouth in a face image).
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] These relationships are needed for identity recognition.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Overlapping the pools so that each feature occurs in multiple pools, helps retain the information.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Translation alone cannot extrapolate the understanding of geometric relationships to a radically new viewpoint, such as a different orientation or scale.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] On the other hand, people are very good at extrapolating; after seeing a new shape once they can recognize it from a different viewpoint.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] An earlier common way to deal with this problem is to train the network on transformed data in different orientations, scales, lighting, etc. so that the network can cope with these variations.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is computationally intensive for large data-sets.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The alternative is to use a hierarchy of coordinate frames and use a group of neurons to represent a conjunction of the shape of the feature and its pose relative to the retina.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The pose relative to the retina is the relationship between the coordinate frame of the retina and the intrinsic features' coordinate frame.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Thus, one way to represent something is to embed the coordinate frame within it.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This allows large features to be recognized by using the consistency of the poses of their parts (e.g. nose and mouth poses make a consistent prediction of the pose of the whole face).
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This approach ensures that the higher-level entity (e.g. face) is present when the lower-level (e.g. nose and mouth) agree on its prediction of the pose.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The vectors of neuronal activity that represent pose ("pose vectors") allow spatial transformations modeled as linear operations that make it easier for the network to learn the hierarchy of visual entities and generalize across viewpoints.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is similar to the way the human visual system imposes coordinate frames in order to represent shapes.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs are often used in image recognition systems.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2012, an error rate of 0.23% on the MNIST database was reported.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper on using CNN for image classification reported that the learning process was "surprisingly fast"; in the same paper, the best published results as of 2011 were achieved in the MNIST database and the NORB database.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, a similar CNN called AlexNet won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] When applied to facial recognition, CNNs achieved a large decrease in error rate.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper reported a 97.6% recognition rate on "5,600 still images of more than 10 subjects".
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs were used to assess video quality in an objective way after manual training; the resulting system had a very low root mean square error.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and hundreds of object classes.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In the ILSVRC 2014, a large-scale visual recognition challenge, almost every highly ranked team used CNN as their basic framework.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The winner GoogLeNet (the foundation of DeepDream) increased the mean average precision of object detection to 0.439329, and reduced classification error to 0.06656, the best result to date.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its network applied more than 30 layers.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] That performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests was close to that of humans.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on a stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters, an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained categories such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, a many-layered CNN demonstrated the ability to spot faces from a wide range of angles, including upside down, even when partially occluded, with competitive performance.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The network was trained on a database of 200,000 images that included faces at various angles and orientations and a further 20 million images without faces.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They used batches of 128 images over 50,000 iterations.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to image data domains, there is relatively little work on applying CNNs to video classification.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Video is more complex than images since it has another (temporal) dimension.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, some extensions of CNNs into the video domain have been explored.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] One approach is to treat space and time as equivalent dimensions of the input and perform convolutions in both time and space.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another way is to fuse the features of two convolutional neural networks, one for the spatial and one for the temporal stream.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Long short-term memory (LSTM) recurrent units are typically incorporated after the CNN to account for inter-frame or inter-clip dependencies.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unsupervised learning schemes for training spatio-temporal features have been introduced, based on convolutional gated restricted Boltzmann machines and independent subspace analysis.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its application can be seen in text-to-video models.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have also been explored for natural language processing.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNN models are effective for various NLP problems and achieved excellent results in semantic parsing, search query retrieval, sentence modeling, classification, prediction and other traditional NLP tasks.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to traditional language processing methods such as recurrent neural networks, CNNs can represent different contextual realities of language that do not rely on a series-sequence assumption, while RNNs are better suitable when classical time series modeling is required.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been applied in ecological and behavioral research to automatically detect and quantify animal behavior from visual data, enabling identification of animals, tracking of individuals, estimation of pose, and classification of specific actions such as feeding, and social interactions.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Combined with multi-object tracking and temporal modeling, these systems can extract behavioral sequences over extended recordings, reducing reliance on manual annotation and increasing throughput for studies of individual variation, social networks, and collective dynamics.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A CNN with 1-D convolutions was used on time series in the frequency domain (spectral residual) by an unsupervised model to detect anomalies in the time domain.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Predicting the interaction between molecules and biological proteins can identify potential treatments.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, Atomwise introduced AtomNet, the first deep learning neural network for structure-based drug design.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The system trains directly on 3-dimensional representations of chemical interactions.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Similar to how image recognition networks learn to compose smaller, spatially proximate features into larger, complex structures, AtomNet discovers chemical features, such as aromaticity, sp3 carbons, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for multiple disease targets, most notably treatments for the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been used in the game of checkers.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] From 1999 to 2001, Fogel and Chellapilla published papers showing how a convolutional neural network could learn to play checkers using co-evolution.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The learning process did not use prior human professional games, but rather focused on a minimal set of information contained in the checkerboard: the location and type of pieces, and the difference in number of pieces between the two sides.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Ultimately, the program (Blondie24) was tested on 165 games against players and ranked in the highest 0.4%.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] It also earned a win against the program Chinook at its "expert" level of play.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In December 2014, Clark and Storkey published a paper showing that a CNN trained by supervised learning from a database of human professional games could outperform GNU Go and win some games against Monte Carlo tree search Fuego 1.1 in a fraction of the time it took Fuego to play.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Later it was announced that a large 12-layer convolutional neural network had correctly predicted the professional move in 55% of positions, equalling the accuracy of a 6 dan human player.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A couple of CNNs for choosing moves to try ("policy network") and evaluating positions ("value network") driving MCTS were used by AlphaGo, the first to beat the best human player at the time.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Recurrent neural networks are generally considered the best neural network architectures for time series forecasting (and sequence modeling in general), but recent studies show that convolutional networks can perform comparably or even better.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Dilated convolutions might enable one-dimensional convolutional neural networks to effectively learn time series dependences.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutions can be implemented more efficiently than RNN-based solutions, and they do not suffer from vanishing (or exploding) gradients.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional networks can provide an improved forecasting performance when there are multiple similar time series to learn from.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs can also be applied to further tasks in time series analysis (e.g., time series classification or quantile forecasting).
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] As archaeological findings such as clay tablets with cuneiform writing are increasingly acquired using 3D scanners, benchmark datasets are becoming available, including *HeiCuBeDa* providing almost 2000 normalized 2-D and 3-D datasets prepared with the GigaMesh Software Framework.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] So curvature-based measures are used in conjunction with geometric neural networks (GNNs), e.g. for period classification of those clay tablets being among the oldest documents of human history.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For many applications, training data is not very available.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional neural networks usually require a large amount of training data in order to avoid overfitting.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A common technique is to train the network on a larger data set from a related domain.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Once the network parameters have converged an additional training step is performed using the in-domain data to fine-tune the network weights, this is known as transfer learning.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Furthermore, this technique allows convolutional network architectures to successfully be applied to problems with tiny training sets.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] End-to-end training and prediction are common practice in computer vision.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, human interpretable explanations are required for critical systems such as self-driving cars.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] With recent advances in visual salience, spatial attention, and temporal attention, the most critical spatial regions/temporal instants could be visualized to justify the CNN predictions.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A deep Q-network (DQN) is a type of deep learning model that combines a deep neural network with Q-learning, a form of reinforcement learning.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unlike earlier reinforcement learning agents, DQNs that utilize CNNs can learn directly from high-dimensional sensory inputs via reinforcement learning.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Preliminary results were presented in 2014, with an accompanying paper in February 2015.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The research described an application to Atari 2600 gaming.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Other deep reinforcement learning models preceded it.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional deep belief networks (CDBN) have structure very similar to convolutional neural networks and are trained similarly to deep belief networks.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Therefore, they exploit the 2D structure of images, like CNNs do, and make use of pre-training like deep belief networks.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They provide a generic structure that can be used in many image and signal processing tasks.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Benchmark results on standard image datasets like CIFAR have been obtained using CDBNs.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The feed-forward architecture of convolutional neural networks was extended in the neural abstraction pyramid by lateral and feedback connections.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The resulting recurrent convolutional network allows for the flexible incorporation of contextual information to iteratively resolve local ambiguities.
[src:image-captioning/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In contrast to previous models, image-like outputs at the highest resolution were generated, e.g., for semantic segmentation, image reconstruction, and object localization tasks.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In deep learning, the **transformer** is a family of artificial neural network architectures based on the multi-head attention mechanism, in which text is converted to numerical representations called tokens, and each token is converted into a vector via lookup from a word embedding table.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] At each layer, each token is then contextualized within the scope of the context window with other (unmasked) tokens via a parallel multi-head attention mechanism, allowing the signal for key tokens to be amplified and less important tokens to be diminished.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Because self-attention alone is permutation-invariant, transformers inject positional information, typically through positional encodings or learned positional embeddings, so token order can affect the output.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Transformers have the advantage of having no recurrent units, therefore requiring less training time than earlier recurrent neural architectures (RNNs) such as long short-term memory (LSTM).
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Later variations have been widely adopted for training large language models (LLMs) on large (language) datasets.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Modern transformer designs are commonly grouped into encoder-only, decoder-only, and encoder-decoder variants, depending on whether they are optimized for representation learning, autoregressive generation, or conditional sequence-to-sequence tasks.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The original version of the transformer architecture was proposed in the 2017 paper "Attention Is All You Need" by researchers at Google.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The predecessors of transformers were developed as an improvement over previous architectures for machine translation, but have found many applications since.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They are used in large-scale natural language processing, computer vision (vision transformers), reinforcement learning, audio, multimodal learning, robotics, and playing chess.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It has also led to the development of pre-trained systems, such as generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) and BERT (bidirectional encoder representations from transformers).
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For many years, sequence modelling and generation was done by using plain recurrent neural networks (RNNs).
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A well-cited early example was the Elman network (1990).
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In theory, the information from one token can propagate arbitrarily far down the sequence, but in practice the vanishing-gradient problem leaves the model's state at the end of a long sentence without precise, extractable information about preceding tokens.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A key breakthrough was LSTM (originally described in a 1995 technical report and formally published in 1997), an RNN that introduced gating mechanisms to mitigate the vanishing gradient problem, allowing efficient learning of long-sequence modelling.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] One key architectural element was the use of *multiplicative gating units*, in which the outputs of some neurons modulate the outputs of others.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] These multiplicative units are conceptually distinct from the additive attention mechanism later introduced for sequence-to-sequence models.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Neural networks using multiplicative units were later called *sigma-pi networks* or *higher-order networks*.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] LSTM became the standard architecture for long sequence modelling until the 2017 publication of transformers.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] However, LSTM still used sequential processing, like most other RNNs.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Specifically, RNNs operate one token at a time from first to last; they cannot operate in parallel over all tokens in a sequence.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Modern transformers overcome this problem, but unlike RNNs, they require computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The linearly scaling fast weight controller (1992) learns to compute a weight matrix for further processing depending on the input.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] One of its two networks has "fast weights" or "dynamic links" (1981).
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A slow neural network learns by gradient descent to generate keys and values for computing the weight changes of the fast neural network which computes answers to queries.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The idea of encoder–decoder sequence transduction had been developed in the early 2010s; commonly cited as the originators that produced seq2seq are two concurrently published papers from 2014.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A 380M-parameter model for machine translation uses two long short-term memories (LSTM).
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The *encoder* is an LSTM that takes in a sequence of tokens and turns it into a vector.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The *decoder* is another LSTM that converts the vector into a sequence of tokens.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Similarly, another 130M-parameter model used gated recurrent units (GRU) instead of LSTM.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Later research showed that GRUs are neither better nor worse than LSTMs for seq2seq.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] These early seq2seq models had no attention mechanism, and the state vector is accessible only after the *last* word of the source text was processed.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Although in theory such a vector retains the information about the whole original sentence, in practice the information is poorly preserved.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is because the input is processed sequentially by one recurrent network into a *fixed*-size output vector, which is then processed by another recurrent network into an output.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] If the input is long, then the output vector would not be able to contain all relevant information, degrading the output.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As evidence, reversing the input sentence improved seq2seq translation.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The *RNN search* model introduced an attention mechanism to seq2seq for machine translation to solve the bottleneck problem (of the *fixed-size* output vector), allowing the model to process long-distance dependencies more easily.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The name is because it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation".
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The relative performances were compared between global (that of *RNN search*) and local (sliding window) attention model architectures for machine translation, finding that mixed attention had higher quality than global attention, while local attention reduced translation time.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In 2016, Google Translate was revamped to Google Neural Machine Translation, which replaced the previous model based on statistical machine translation.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The new model was a seq2seq model where the encoder and the decoder were both 8 layers of bidirectional LSTM.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It took nine months to develop, and it outperformed the statistical approach, which took ten years to develop.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Seq2seq models with attention (including self-attention) still suffered from the same issue with recurrent networks, which is that they are hard to parallelize, which prevented them from being accelerated on GPUs.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In 2016, *decomposable attention* applied a self-attention mechanism to feedforward networks, which are easy to parallelize, and achieved SOTA result in textual entailment with an order of magnitude fewer parameters than LSTMs.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] One of its authors, Jakob Uszkoreit, suspected that attention *without* recurrence would be sufficient for language translation, thus the title "attention is *all* you need".
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] That hypothesis was against conventional wisdom at the time, and even his father Hans Uszkoreit, a well-known computational linguist, was skeptical.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In the same year, self-attention (called *intra-attention or* *intra-sentence attention*) was proposed for LSTMs.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] On 2017-06-12, the original (100M-parameter) encoder–decoder transformer model was published in the "Attention is all you need" paper.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] At the time, the focus of the research was on improving seq2seq for machine translation, by removing its recurrence to process all tokens in parallel, but preserving its dot-product attention mechanism to keep its text processing performance.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This led to the introduction of a multi-head attention model that was easier to parallelize due to the use of independent heads and the lack of recurrence.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Its parallelizability was an important factor to its widespread use in large neural networks.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As early as spring 2017, even before the "Attention is all you need" preprint was published, one of the co-authors applied the "decoder-only" variation of the architecture to generate fictitious Wikipedia articles.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Transformer architecture is now used alongside many generative models that contribute to the ongoing AI boom.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The "reference implementation" of the original Transformer was written in a TensorFlow library.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In language modelling, ELMo (2018) was a bi-directional LSTM that produces contextualized word embeddings, improving upon the line of research from bag of words and word2vec.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It was followed by BERT (2018), an encoder-only transformer model.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In October 2019, Google started using BERT to process search queries.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model by a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Starting in 2018, the OpenAI GPT series of decoder-only transformers became state of the art in natural language generation.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] At the end of 2022, ChatGPT, a chatbot based on a fine-tuned variant of GPT-3.5, became unexpectedly popular, triggering a boom around large language models.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Transformers have been applied in modalities beyond text.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Four days after the publication of "Attention is All You Need", a multimodal transformer architecture, MultiModel, was published by most authors of that paper.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Other examples include the vision transformer, speech recognition, robotics, and multimodal.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The vision transformer, in turn, stimulated new developments in convolutional neural networks.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The plain transformer architecture had difficulty in converging.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In the original paper, the authors recommended using learning rate warmup.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] That is, the learning rate should linearly scale up from 0 to maximal value for the first part of the training (usually recommended to be 2% of the total number of training steps), before decaying again.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A 2020 paper found that using layer normalization *before* (instead of after) multihead attention and feedforward layers stabilizes training, not requiring learning rate warmup.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is the "pre-LN Transformer" and is more commonly used, compared to the original "post-LN Transformer".
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Transformers typically are first pretrained by self-supervised learning on a large generic dataset, followed by supervised fine-tuning on a small task-specific dataset.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The pretrain dataset is typically an unlabeled large corpus, such as The Pile.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The T5 transformer report documents a large number of natural language pretraining tasks.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Note that while each of these tasks is trivial or obvious for human native speakers of the language (or languages), they have typically proved challenging for previous generations of machine learning architecture.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In general, there are 3 classes of language modelling tasks: "masked", "autoregressive", and "prefixLM".
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] These classes are independent of a specific modeling architecture such as transformer, but they are often discussed in the context of transformer.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In a masked task, one or more of the tokens is masked out, and the model would produce a probability distribution predicting what the masked-out tokens are based on the context.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The loss function for the task is typically sum of log-perplexities for the masked-out tokens: ${\text{Loss}}=-\sum _{t\in {\text{masked tokens}}}\ln({\text{probability of }}t{\text{ conditional on its context}})$ and the model is trained to minimize this loss function.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The BERT series of models are trained for masked token prediction and another task.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In an autoregressive task, the entire sequence is masked at first, and the model produces a probability distribution for the first token.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Then the first token is revealed and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The loss function for the task is still typically the same.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The GPT series of models are trained by autoregressive tasks.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In a prefixLM task, the sequence is divided into two parts.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The first part is presented as context, and the model predicts the first token of the second part.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Then that would be revealed, and the model predicts the second token, and so on.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The T5 series of models are trained by prefixLM tasks.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Note that "masked" as in "masked language modelling" is not "masked" as in "masked attention", and "prefixLM" as in "prefix language modeling" is not "prefixLM" as in " prefix language model".
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The following description follows exactly the transformer as described in the original paper.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] There are variants, described in the following section.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] By convention, we write all vectors as row vectors.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For example, pushing a vector through a linear layer means multiplying it by a weight matrix on the right, as $xW$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As the transformer architecture natively consists of operations over numbers (matrix multiplications, dot products, activation functions) rather than over text, there must first be a mapping from any input text to some numerical representation.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] First, the input text is treated by a *preprocessor*, which performs both textual transformations and splits the text into coarse-grained segments called *pretokens*.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The latter is referred to as *pretokenization*.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Second, each pretoken is segmented further into *tokens* by a *tokenizer* that expects to only see pretokens output by its preprocessor.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each token it produces is a string of one or more characters belonging to a finite set of strings called the *vocabulary* V .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Third, because the vocabulary is finite and known beforehand, each token can be assigned an integer identifier, and this mapping is applied to the sequence of tokens to represent any input text as a numerical sequence.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Since this mapping is bijective, the output side can produce a sequence of integer identifiers which can then be turned back into tokens.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] After undoing some of the preprocessing, the result is again legible text.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Training a tokenizer (sometimes referred to as *vocabularization*) means finding a suitable vocabulary V , but also learning how to use it, since any given string s of length $|s|$ has $2^{|s|-1}$ hypothetical segmentations, some of which containing segments that are not in the vocabulary.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The most important hyperparameter during vocabularization is the *vocabulary size* $|V|$ : when it is small, the learned vocabulary generally consists of characters and smaller strings, and words will be segmented into many tokens.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] At larger sizes, it becomes affordable to dedicate tokens to full words, although depending on the preprocessor and tokenizer, it is not necessarily the case that large vocabularies will always use the largest token(s) available to segment a word.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Because tokens are not always full words, they may also be referred to as *subwords* and tokenization algorithms may be referred to as *subword tokenizers*.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is also to differentiate these systems from traditional terminology used in older information retrieval and natural language processing systems, where "tokenization" was used to denote what is today called "pretokenization" (very crudely: splitting into words).
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In tokenizers that produce tokens that are *not* part of the vocabulary, a special token that does belong to the vocabulary is used as a generic stand-in, written as "[UNK]" for "unknown".
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In principle, any string could be hidden by such an [UNK].
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Indeed, in information retrieval, pretokenizers were themselves used as tokenizers (and also called "tokenizers") with a word-level vocabulary that contained an [UNK].
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Commonly used subword tokenization algorithms are byte pair encoding (BPE) and the unigram language model (ULM), which each include a vocabularization algorithm and a dedicated segmentation algorithm.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] There also exist several segmentation algorithms that require no learning and can be applied given a vocabulary (produced by BPE or ULM, for example), like greedily recognising tokens in a pretoken by moving through it left-to-right.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Well-known software implementations of subword tokenizers are Hugging Face's `tokenizers` Python package implemented in Rust, and the `sentencepiece` Python package implemented in C++.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The latter package is named as such because one of its configuration options allows disabling the built-in pretokenizer, hence effectively making entire sentences a pretoken and thus having the tokenizer see entire sentences, rather than individual words.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each integer token identifier is converted into an embedding vector via a lookup table.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Equivalently stated, it multiplies a one-hot representation of the token identifier by an embedding matrix M .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The dimension of an embedding vector is called *hidden size* or *embedding size* and written as $d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This size is written as $d_{\text{model}}$ in the original transformer paper.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] An un-embedding layer is almost the reverse of an embedding layer.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Whereas an embedding layer converts a token identifier into a vector, an un-embedding layer converts a vector into a probability distribution over tokens.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The un-embedding layer is a linear-softmax layer: $\mathrm {UnEmbed} (x)=\mathrm {softmax} (xW+b)$ The matrix has shape $(d_{\text{emb}},|V|)$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Some architectures use the transpose of the embedding matrix M as the un-embedding matrix W in order to avoid needing double the amount of embedding-related parameters and to avoid divergence during training.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A positional encoding is a fixed-size vector representation of the relative positions of tokens within a sequence: it provides the transformer model with information about *where* the words are in the input sequence.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This induces a bias towards the order of the input sequence, so that, for example, the input sequence "man bites dog" is processed differently from "dog bites man".
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The positional encoding is defined as a function of type $f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , where d is a positive even integer.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Here, N is a free parameter that should be significantly larger than the biggest k that would be input into the positional encoding function.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The main reason for using this positional encoding function is that using it, shifts are linear transformations: $f(t+\Delta t)=\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t))f(t)$ where $\Delta t\in \mathbb {R}$ is the distance one wishes to shift.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position, and find the encoding of the position n-steps-ahead or n-steps-behind, by a matrix multiplication.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] By taking a linear sum, any convolution can also be implemented as linear transformations: $\sum _{j}c_{j}f(t+\Delta t_{j})=\left(\sum _{j}c_{j}\,\mathrm {diag} (f(\Delta t_{j}))\right)f(t)$ for any constants $c_{j}$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This allows the transformer to take any encoded position and find a linear sum of the encoded locations of its neighbors.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This sum of encoded positions, when fed into the attention mechanism, would create attention weights on its neighbors, much like what happens in a convolutional neural network language model.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In typical implementations, all operations are done over the real numbers, not the complex numbers, but since complex multiplication can be implemented as real 2-by-2 matrix multiplication, this is a mere notational difference.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Like earlier seq2seq models, the original transformer model used an **encoder–decoder** architecture.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The encoder consists of encoding layers that process all the input tokens together one layer after another, while the decoder consists of decoding layers that iteratively process the encoder's output and the decoder's output tokens so far.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The purpose of each encoder layer is to create contextualized representations of the tokens, where each representation corresponds to a token that "mixes" information from other input tokens via self-attention mechanism.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Both the encoder and decoder layers have a feed-forward neural network for additional processing of their outputs and contain residual connections and layer normalization steps.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] These feed-forward layers contain most of the parameters in a transformer model.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The feedforward network (FFN) modules in a transformer are 2-layered multilayer perceptrons: $\mathrm {FFN} (x)=\phi (xW^{(1)}+b^{(1)})W^{(2)}+b^{(2)}$ where $W^{(1)}$ and $W^{(2)}$ are weight matrices and $b^{(1)}$ and $b^{(2)}$ are bias vectors, and $\phi$ is its activation function.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The original transformer used ReLU activation.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The number of neurons in the middle layer is called *intermediate size* (GPT), *filter size* (BERT), or *feedforward size* (BERT).
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It is typically larger than the embedding size.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For example, in both GPT-2 series and BERT series, the intermediate size of a model is 4 times its embedding size: $d_{\text{ffn}}=4d_{\text{emb}}$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The attention mechanism used in the transformer architecture are scaled dot-product attention units.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For each unit, the transformer model learns three weight matrices: the query weights $W^{Q}$ , the key weights $W^{K}$ , and the value weights $W^{V}$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The module takes three sequences, a query sequence, a key sequence, and a value sequence.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The query sequence is a sequence of length $\ell _{\text{seq, query}}$ , and each entry is a vector of dimension $d_{\text{emb, query}}$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Similarly for the key and value sequences.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For each vector $x_{i,{\text{query}}}$ in the query sequence, it is multiplied by a matrix $W^{Q}$ to produce a query vector $q_{i}=x_{i,{\text{query}}}W^{Q}$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The matrix of all query vectors is the query matrix: $Q=X_{\text{query}}W^{Q}$ Similarly, we construct the key matrix $K=X_{\text{key}}W^{K}$ and the value matrix $V=X_{\text{value}}W^{V}$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It is usually the case that all $W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}$ are square matrices, meaning $d_{\text{emb, query}}=d_{\text{query}}$ , etc.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Attention weights are calculated using the query and key vectors: the attention weight $a_{ij}$ from token i to token j is the dot product between $q_{i}$ and $k_{j}$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The attention weights are divided by the square root of the dimension of the key vectors, ${\sqrt {d_{k}}}$ , which stabilizes gradients during training, and passed through a softmax which normalizes the weights.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The fact that $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ are different matrices allows attention to be non-symmetric: if token i attends to token j (i.e. $q_{i}\cdot k_{j}$ is large), this does not necessarily mean that token j will attend to token i (i.e. $q_{j}\cdot k_{i}$ could be small).
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The output of the attention unit for token i is the weighted sum of the value vectors of all tokens, weighted by $a_{ij}$ , the attention from token i to each token.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The attention calculation for all tokens can be expressed as one large matrix calculation using the softmax function, which is useful for training due to computational matrix operation optimizations that quickly compute matrix operations.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The matrices Q , K and V are defined as the matrices where the i th rows are vectors $q_{i}$ , $k_{i}$ , and $v_{i}$ respectively.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] where the softmax is applied over each of the rows of the matrix.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The number of dimensions in a query vector is *query size* $d_{\text{query}}$ and similarly for the *key size* $d_{\text{key}}$ and *value size* $d_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The output dimension of an attention head is its *head dimension* $d_{\text{head}}$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The attention mechanism requires the following three equalities to hold: $\ell _{\text{seq, key}}=\ell _{\text{seq, value}},\;d_{\text{query}}=d_{\text{key}},\;d_{\text{value}}=d_{\text{head}}$ but is otherwise unconstrained.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] If the attention head is used in a self-attention fashion, then $X_{\text{query}}=X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] If the attention head is used in a cross-attention fashion, then usually $X_{\text{query}}\neq X_{\text{key}}=X_{\text{value}}$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It is theoretically possible for all three to be different, but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] One set of $\left(W^{Q},W^{K},W^{V}\right)$ matrices is called an *attention head*, and each layer in a transformer model has multiple attention heads.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] While each attention head attends to the tokens that are relevant to each token, multiple attention heads allow the model to do this for different definitions of "relevance".
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Specifically, the query and key projection matrices, $W^{Q}$ and $W^{K}$ , which are involved in the attention score computation, defines the "relevance".
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Meanwhile, the value projection matrix $W^{V}$ , in combination with the part of the output projection matrix $W^{O}$ , determines how the attended tokens influence what information is passed to subsequent layers and ultimately the output logits.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In addition, the scope of attention, or the range of token relationships captured by each attention head, can expand as tokens pass through successive layers.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This allows the model to capture more complex and long-range dependencies in deeper layers.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Many transformer attention heads encode relevance relations that are meaningful to humans.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For example, some attention heads can attend mostly to the next word, while others mainly attend from verbs to their direct objects.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The computations for each attention head can be performed in parallel, which allows for fast processing.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The outputs for the attention layer are concatenated to pass into the feedforward neural network layers.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It is theoretically possible for each attention head to have a different head dimension $d_{\text{head}}$ , but that is rarely the case in practice.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As an example, in the smallest GPT-2 model, there are only self-attention mechanisms.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The transformer architecture is constructed to calculate output tokens iteratively.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Assuming $t=0$ refers to the calculation of the first output token $i=0$ , for step $t>0$ , the output token $i=0$ shall remain constant.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This ensures properties of the model similar to autoregressive models.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Therefore, at every time step t , the calculation for all outputs i should not have access to tokens at position j for $j>=i$ (as it naturally is the case for time step $t=i$ , when tokens $j>t$ are not yet calculated).
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In words, it means that each token can pay attention to itself, and every token before it, but not any after it.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A non-masked attention module can be thought of as a masked attention module where the mask has all entries zero.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As an example of an uncommon use of mask matrix, the XLNet considers all masks of the form $PM_{\text{causal}}P^{-1}$ , where P is a random permutation matrix.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] An encoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple encoder layers.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each encoder layer consists of two major components: a self-attention mechanism and a feed-forward layer.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It takes an input as a sequence of input vectors, applies the self-attention mechanism, to produce an intermediate sequence of vectors, then applies the feed-forward layer for each vector individually.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] where ${\text{FFN}}$ stands for "feed-forward network".
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] We can more succinctly write it as ${\text{EncoderLayer}}(H)={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H))$ with the implicit convention that the ${\text{FFN}}$ is applied to each row of the matrix individually.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The first encoder layer takes the sequence of input vectors from the embedding layer, producing a sequence of vectors.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This sequence of vectors is processed by the second encoder, and so on.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The output from the final encoder layer is then used by the decoder.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] As the encoder processes the entire input all at once, every token can attend to every other token (all-to-all attention), so there is no need for causal masking.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A decoder consists of an embedding layer, followed by multiple decoder layers, followed by an un-embedding layer.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each decoder consists of three major components: a causally masked self-attention mechanism, a cross-attention mechanism, and a feed-forward neural network.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The decoder functions in a similar fashion to the encoder, but an additional attention mechanism is inserted which instead draws relevant information from the encodings generated by the encoders.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This mechanism can also be called the *encoder–decoder attention*.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Like the first encoder, the first decoder takes positional information and embeddings of the output sequence as its input, rather than encodings.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The transformer must not use the current or future output to predict an output, so the output sequence must be partially masked to prevent this reverse information flow.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This allows for autoregressive text generation.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For decoding, all-to-all attention is inappropriate, because a token cannot attend to tokens not yet generated.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Thus, the self-attention module in the decoder is causally masked.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In contrast, the cross-attention mechanism attends to the output vectors of the encoder, which is computed before the decoder starts decoding.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Consequently, there is no need for masking in the cross-attention mechanism.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Schematically, we have: ${\begin{aligned}H'&={\text{MaskedMultiheadAttention}}(H,H,H)\\{\text{DecoderLayer}}(H)&={\text{FFN}}({\text{MultiheadAttention}}(H',H^{E},H^{E}))\end{aligned}}$ where $H^{E}$ is the matrix with rows being the output vectors from the encoder.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The last decoder is followed by a final un-embedding layer to produce the output probabilities over the vocabulary.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Then, one of the tokens is sampled according to the probability, and the decoder can be run again to produce the next token, etc., autoregressively generating output text.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each encoder layer contains 2 sublayers: the self-attention and the feedforward network.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Each decoder layer contains 3 sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, the cross-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The final points of detail are the residual connections and layer normalization, (denoted as "LayerNorm", or "LN" in the following), which while conceptually unnecessary, are necessary for numerical stability and convergence.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The residual connections are introduced to avoid vanishing gradient issues and stabilize the training process.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They can be expressed by $x\mapsto F(x)+x$ , where F is a given component of the transformer.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Adding the input x can preserve the input information and avoid issues when the gradient of $F(x)$ is close to zero.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Similarly to how the feedforward network modules are applied individually to each vector, the LayerNorm is also applied individually to each vector.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] There are two common conventions in use: the *post-LN* and the *pre-LN* convention.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In the post-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (x))$ where $\mathrm {Sublayer} (x)$ is the function implemented by the sublayer itself.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] In the pre-LN convention, the output of each sublayer is $x+\mathrm {Sublayer} (\mathrm {LayerNorm} (x))$ The original 2017 transformer used the post-LN convention.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] It was difficult to train and required careful hyperparameter tuning and a "warm-up" in learning rate, where it starts small and gradually increases.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The pre-LN convention, proposed several times in 2018, was found to be easier to train, requiring no warm-up, leading to faster convergence.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The transformer architecture, being modular, allows variations.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Several common variations are described here.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] An "encoder-only" transformer applies the encoder to map an input text into a sequence of vectors that represent the input text.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is usually used for text embedding and representation learning for downstream applications.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They are less often used currently, as they were found to be not significantly better than training an encoder–decoder transformer, then taking just the encoder.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They are also referred to as "all-to-all" or "BERT-like".
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A "decoder-only" transformer is not literally decoder-only, since without an encoder, the cross-attention mechanism has nothing to attend to.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Thus, the decoder layers in a decoder-only transformer is composed of just two sublayers: the causally masked self-attention, and the feedforward network.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The models in the GPT series and Chinchilla series are decoder-only.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They are also referred to as "autoregressive" or "causal".
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] An "encoder–decoder" transformer is generally the same as the original transformer, with 2 sublayers per encoder layer and 3 sublayers per decoder layer, etc.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They might have minor architectural improvements, such as alternative activation functions, changing the location of normalization, etc.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] This is also usually used for text generation and instruction following.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] The models in the T5 series are encoder–decoder.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] A "prefixLM" (prefix language model) is a decoder-only architecture, but with prefix masking, which is different from causal masking.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Specifically, it has mask of the form $M_{\text{prefixLM}}={\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf {0} &-\infty \\\mathbf {0} &M_{\text{causal}}\end{bmatrix}}$ where the first columns correspond to the "prefix", and the subsequent columns correspond to the autoregressively generated text based on the prefix.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] They resemble encoder–decoder models, but has less "sparsity".
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] Such models are rarely used, though they are cited as theoretical possibilities and benchmarked comparisons.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p01] For example, in 2020, Google Translate replaced the previous RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model with a transformer-encoder–RNN-decoder model, as transformer-based decoders did not appear to significantly increase quality unlike the encoder, while the RNN decoder was much faster.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The original transformer uses ReLU activation function.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Other activation functions were developed.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The Llama series and PaLM used SwiGLU; both GPT-1 and BERT used GELU.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Alternative activation functions are often used in combination with Gated Linear Units in the feedforward module.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The normalization used in the transformer can be different from LayerNorm.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] One example is RMSNorm which is used in the Llama series.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Other examples include ScaleNorm and FixNorm.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Transformers may use other positional encoding methods than sinusoidal.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The original transformer paper reported using a learned positional encoding, but finding it not superior to the sinusoidal one.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Later, found that causal masking itself provides enough signal to a transformer decoder that it can learn to implicitly perform absolute positional encoding without the positional encoding module.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Then the RoPE encoding is applied to each pair of coordinates.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The benefit of RoPE is that the dot-product between two vectors depends on their relative location only: ${\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n{\big )}={\text{RoPE}}{\big (}x,m+k{\big )}^{T}{\text{RoPE}}{\big (}y,n+k{\big )}$ for any integer k .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] ALiBi (Attention with Linear Biases) is not a *replacement* for the positional encoder on the original transformer.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Instead, it is an *additional* positional encoder that is directly plugged into the attention mechanism.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The idea being that the linear bias matrix is a softened mask.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Just as 0 represent full attention paid, and $-\infty$ represents no attention paid, the linear bias matrix increases attention paid in one direction and decreases attention paid in the other direction.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] ALiBi allows pretraining on short context windows, then fine-tuning on longer context windows.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Since it is directly plugged into the attention mechanism, it can be combined with any positional encoder that is plugged into the "bottom" of the entire network (which is where the sinusoidal encoder on the original transformer, as well as RoPE and many others, are located).
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Relative Position Encodings is similar to ALiBi, but more generic: ${\begin{aligned}{\text{Attention}}(Q,K,V)={\text{softmax}}\left({\frac {QK^{\mathrm {T} }}{\sqrt {d_{k}}}}+B\right)V\end{aligned}}$ where B is a Toeplitz matrix, that is, $B_{i,j}=B_{i',j'}$ whenever $i-j=i'-j'$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] This is contrasted with the original sinusoidal positional encoding, which is an "absolute positional encoding".
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The transformer model has been implemented in standard deep learning frameworks such as TensorFlow and PyTorch.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] *Transformers* is a library produced by Hugging Face that supplies transformer-based architectures and pretrained models.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] When an autoregressive transformer is used for inference, such as generating text, the query vector is different at each step, but the already-computed key and value vectors are always the same.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The **KV caching** method saves the computed key and value vectors at each attention block, so that they are not recomputed at each new token.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] PagedAttention applies memory paging to KV caching.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] If a transformer is used with a baked-in prompt, such as ["You are a customer support agent..."], then the key and value vectors can be computed for the prompt, and saved on disk.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The saving in compute is significant when the model is used for many short real-time interactions, such as in online chatbots.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In general, when a user uses an autoregressive transformer to generate a continuation to a sequence of tokens, the model would first perform a forward-pass on this sequence, whereby the KV caches over this sequence are computed.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Hyperscalers serving large Transformer models may use **disaggregated inference**, wherein prefilling and decoding are performed on separately specialized hardware.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] FlashAttention is an algorithm that implements the transformer attention mechanism efficiently on a GPU.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] It is a communication-avoiding algorithm that performs matrix multiplications in blocks, such that each block fits within the cache of a GPU, and by careful management of the blocks it minimizes data copying between GPU caches (as data movement is slow).
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The FlashAttention method is a communication-avoiding algorithm that fuses these operations into a single loop, increasing the arithmetic intensity.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In practice, FlashAttention operates over multiple queries and keys per loop iteration, in a similar way as blocked matrix multiplication.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] If backpropagation is needed, then the output vectors and the intermediate arrays $[m_{1},\dots ,m_{N}],[\ell _{1},\dots ,\ell _{N}]$ are cached, and during the backward pass, attention matrices are rematerialized from these, making it a form of gradient checkpointing.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] An improved version, FlashAttention-2, was developed to cater to the rising demand for language models capable of handling longer context lengths.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] It offers enhancements in work partitioning and parallelism, enabling it to achieve up to 230 TFLOPs/s on A100 GPUs (FP16/BF16), a 2x speed increase over the original FlashAttention.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Key advancements in FlashAttention-2 include the reduction of non-matmul FLOPs, improved parallelism over the sequence length dimension, better work partitioning between GPU warps, and added support for head dimensions up to 256 and multi-query attention (MQA) and grouped-query attention (GQA).
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Benchmarks revealed FlashAttention-2 to be up to 2x faster than FlashAttention and up to 9x faster than a standard attention implementation in PyTorch.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Future developments include optimization for new hardware like H100 GPUs and new data types like FP8.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] FlashAttention-4 focuses on pipelining to increase instruction throughput, and was developed to perform particularly well on Blackwell GPUs.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Multi-Query Attention changes the Multihead Attention mechanism.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] This has a neutral effect on model quality and training speed, but increases inference speed.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] More generally, grouped-query attention (GQA) partitions attention heads into groups, each of which shares the key-value pair.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] MQA is GQA with one group, while standard Multihead Attention is GQA with the maximal number of groups.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Multihead Latent Attention (MLA) is a low-rank approximation to standard MHA.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Specifically, each hidden vector, before entering the attention mechanism, is first projected to two low-dimensional spaces ("latent space"), one for query and one for key-value (KV vector).
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] This design minimizes the KV cache, as only the low-dimensional KV vector needs to be cached.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Speculative decoding is a method to accelerate token decoding.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Similarly to speculative execution in CPUs, future tokens are computed quickly, then verified.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] If the quickly computed tokens are incorrect, they are discarded and computed slowly.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The key factor in speculative decoding is that a transformer decoder can verify faster than it can decode, in the following sense.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Suppose we have two transformer models like GPT-3 and GPT-3-small, both with a context window size of 512.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] To generate an entire context window autoregressively with greedy decoding with GPT-3, it must be run for 512 times, each time generating a token $x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{512}$ , taking time $512T_{\text{GPT-3}}$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] However, if we had some educated guess for the values of these tokens, we could verify all of them in parallel, in one run of the model, by checking that each $x_{t}$ is indeed the token with the largest log-likelihood in the t -th output.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In speculative decoding, a smaller model or some other simple heuristic is used to generate a few speculative tokens that are subsequently verified by the larger model.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] These tokens are then run through the larger GPT-3 in one go.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Suppose that ${\tilde {x}}_{1}$ and ${\tilde {x}}_{2}$ are verified by GPT-3 as what it would have picked, then those are kept, but ${\tilde {x}}_{3}$ is not, so ${\tilde {x}}_{3},{\tilde {x}}_{4}$ are discarded, and GPT-3 is run on those.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] For non-greedy decoding, similar ideas apply, except the speculative tokens are accepted or rejected stochastically, in a way that guarantees the final output distribution is the same as if speculative decoding was not used.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In Multi-Token Prediction, a single forward pass creates a final embedding vector, which then is un-embedded into a token probability.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] However, that vector can then be further processed by another transformer block to predict the *next* token, and so on for arbitrarily many steps into the future.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] This trades off accuracy for speed, since each new token costs just one more transformer block, rather than the entire stack.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Training transformer-based architectures can be expensive, especially for long inputs.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Many methods have been developed to attempt to address the issue.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In the image domain, Swin transformer is an efficient architecture that performs attention inside shifting windows.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] In the audio domain, SepTr decouples the attention in time and frequency domains.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] *Long Range Arena* (2020) is a standard benchmark for comparing the behavior of transformer architectures over long inputs.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The standard attention graph is either all-to-all or causal, both of which scales as $O(N^{2})$ where N is the number of tokens in a sequence.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Reformer (2020) reduces the computational load from $O(N^{2})$ to $O(N\ln N)$ by using locality-sensitive hashing and reversible layers.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Sparse attention uses attention graphs that grows slower than $O(N^{2})$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] For example, BigBird (2020) uses random small-world networks which grows as $O(N)$ .
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Ordinary transformers require a memory size that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Attention-free transformers reduce this to a linear dependence while still retaining the advantages of a transformer by linking the key to the value.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Similarly for multiple queries, and for multihead attention.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] This approximation can be computed in linear time, as we can compute the matrix $\varphi (k_{i})v_{i}^{T}$ first, then multiply it with the query.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Transformers can also be used/adapted for modalities (input or output) beyond just text, usually by finding a way to "tokenize" the modality.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Multimodal models can either be trained from scratch, or by finetuning.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] A 2022 study found that transformers pretrained only on natural language can be finetuned on only 0.03% of parameters and become competitive with LSTMs on a variety of logical and visual tasks, demonstrating transfer learning.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The LLaVA was a vision-language model composed of a language model (Vicuna-13B) and a vision model (ViT-L/14), connected by a linear layer.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Vision transformers adapt the transformer to computer vision by breaking down input images as a series of patches, turning them into vectors, and treating them like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Conformer and later Whisper follow the same pattern for speech recognition, first turning the speech signal into a spectrogram, which is then treated like an image, i.e. broken down into a series of patches, turned into vectors and treated like embedding vector of tokens in a standard transformer.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Perceivers are a variant of transformers designed for multimodality.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] For image generation, notable architectures are DALL-E 1 (2021), Parti (2022), Phenaki (2023), and Muse (2023).
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Unlike later models, DALL-E is not a diffusion model.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Instead, it uses a decoder-only transformer that autoregressively generates a text, followed by the token representation of an image, which is then converted by a variational autoencoder to an image.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Parti is an encoder–decoder transformer, where the encoder processes a text prompt, and the decoder generates a token representation of an image.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] Muse is an encoder-only transformer that is trained to predict masked image tokens from unmasked image tokens.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] During generation, all input tokens are masked, and the highest-confidence predictions are included for the next iteration, until all tokens are predicted.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] It is a bidirectional masked transformer conditioned on pre-computed text tokens.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The generated tokens are then decoded to a video.
[src:image-captioning/encoder-decoder-model-p02] The transformer has had great success in natural language processing (NLP).
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] While it is widely agreed that the output of any NLG process is text, there is some disagreement about whether the inputs of an NLG system need to be non-linguistic.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Common applications of NLG methods include the production of various reports, for example weather and patient reports; image captions; and chatbots like ChatGPT.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Automated NLG can be compared to the process humans use when they turn ideas into writing or speech.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Psycholinguists prefer the term language production for this process, which can also be described in mathematical terms, or modeled in a computer for psychological research.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] NLG systems can also be compared to translators of artificial computer languages, such as decompilers or transpilers, which also produce human-readable code generated from an intermediate representation.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Human languages tend to be considerably more complex and allow for much more ambiguity and variety of expression than programming languages, which makes NLG more challenging.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] The practical considerations in building NLU vs.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] NLU needs to deal with ambiguous or erroneous user input, whereas the ideas the system wants to express through NLG are generally known precisely.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] NLG needs to choose a specific, self-consistent textual representation from many potential representations, whereas NLU generally tries to produce a single, normalized representation of the idea expressed.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] NLG has existed since ELIZA was developed in the mid 1960s, but the methods were first used commercially in the 1990s.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] NLG techniques range from simple template-based systems like a mail merge that generates form letters, to systems that have a complex understanding of human grammar.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] NLG can also be accomplished by training a statistical model using machine learning, typically on a large corpus of human-written texts.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] The *Pollen Forecast for Scotland* system is a simple example of a simple NLG system that could essentially be based on a template.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] This system takes as input six numbers, which give predicted pollen levels in different parts of Scotland.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] From these numbers, the system generates a short textual summary of pollen levels as its output.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Comparing these two illustrates some of the choices that NLG systems must make; these are further discussed below.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] The process to generate text can be as simple as keeping a list of canned text that is copied and pasted, possibly linked with some glue text.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] The results may be satisfactory in simple domains such as horoscope machines or generators of personalized business letters.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] However, a sophisticated NLG system needs to include stages of planning and merging of information to enable the generation of text that looks natural and does not become repetitive.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Deciding what information to mention in the text.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] For instance, in the pollen example above, deciding whether to explicitly mention that pollen level is 7 in the southeast.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Overall organisation of the information to convey.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] For example, deciding to describe the areas with high pollen levels first, instead of the areas with low pollen levels.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Merging of similar sentences to improve readability and naturalness.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] should be used when describing a pollen level of 4.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] to refer to a certain region in Scotland.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] An alternative approach to NLG is to use "end-to-end" machine learning to build a system, without having separate stages as above.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] In other words, we build an NLG system by training a machine learning algorithm (often an LSTM) on a large data set of input data and corresponding (human-written) output texts.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] The end-to-end approach has perhaps been most successful in image captioning, that is automatically generating a textual caption for an image.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] From a commercial perspective, the most successful NLG applications have been *data-to-text* systems which generate textual summaries of databases and data sets; these systems usually perform data analysis as well as text generation.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Research has shown that textual summaries can be more effective than graphs and other visuals for decision support, and that computer-generated texts can be superior (from the reader's perspective) to human-written texts.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] The first commercial data-to-text systems produced weather forecasts from weather data.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] The earliest such system to be deployed was FoG, which was used by Environment Canada to generate weather forecasts in French and English in the early 1990s.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] The success of FoG triggered other work, both research and commercial.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Recent applications include the UK Met Office's text-enhanced forecast.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Data-to-text systems have since been applied in a range of settings.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Following the minor earthquake near Beverly Hills, California on March 17, 2014, The Los Angeles Times reported details about the time, location and strength of the quake within 3 minutes of the event.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] This report was automatically generated by a 'robo-journalist', which converted the incoming data into text via a preset template.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Currently there is considerable commercial interest in using NLG to summarise financial and business data.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Indeed, Gartner has said that NLG will become a standard feature of 90% of modern BI and analytics platforms.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] NLG is also being used commercially in automated journalism, chatbots, generating product descriptions for e-commerce sites, summarising medical records, and enhancing accessibility (for example by describing graphs and data sets to blind people).
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] An example of an interactive use of NLG is the WYSIWYM framework.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] It stands for *What you see is what you meant* and allows users to see and manipulate the continuously rendered view (NLG output) of an underlying formal language document (NLG input), thereby editing the formal language without learning it.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Looking ahead, the current progress in data-to-text generation paves the way for tailoring texts to specific audiences.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] For example, data from babies in neonatal care can be converted into text differently in a clinical setting, with different levels of technical detail and explanatory language, depending on intended recipient of the text (doctor, nurse, patient).
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] The same idea can be applied in a sports setting, with different reports generated for fans of specific teams.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Over the past few years, there has been an increased interest in automatically generating captions for images, as part of a broader endeavor to investigate the interface between vision and language.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] A case of data-to-text generation, the algorithm of image captioning (or automatic image description) involves taking an image, analyzing its visual content, and generating a textual description (typically a sentence) that verbalizes the most prominent aspects of the image.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] An image captioning system involves two sub-tasks.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] In Image Analysis, features and attributes of an image are detected and labelled, before mapping these outputs to linguistic structures.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Recent research utilize*s* deep learning approaches through features from a pre-trained convolutional neural network such as AlexNet, VGG or Caffe, where caption generators use an activation layer from the pre-trained network as their input features.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Text Generation, the second task, is performed using a wide range of techniques.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] For example, in the Midge system, input images are represented as triples consisting of object/stuff detections, action/pose detections and spatial relations.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] These are subsequently mapped to <noun, verb, preposition> triples and realized using a tree substitution grammar.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] A common method in image captioning is to use a vision model (such as a ResNet) to encode an image into a vector, then use a language model (such as an RNN) to decode the vector into a caption.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Despite advancements, challenges and opportunities remain in image capturing research.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Other open challenges include visual question-answering (VQA), as well as the construction and evaluation multilingual repositories for image description.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Another area where NLG has been widely applied is automated dialogue systems, frequently in the form of chatbots.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] A chatbot or chatterbot is a software application used to conduct an on-line chat conversation via text or text-to-speech, in lieu of providing direct contact with a live human agent.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] While natural language processing (NLP) techniques are applied in deciphering human input, NLG informs the output part of the chatbot algorithms in facilitating real-time dialogues.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Early chatbot systems, including Cleverbot created by Rollo Carpenter in 1988 and published in 1997, reply to questions by identifying how a human has responded to the same question in a conversation database using information retrieval (IR) techniques.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Modern chatbot systems predominantly rely on machine learning (ML) models, such as sequence-to-sequence learning and reinforcement learning to generate natural language output.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] For example, the Alibaba shopping assistant first uses an IR approach to retrieve the best candidates from the knowledge base, then uses the ML-driven seq2seq model re-rank the candidate responses and generate the answer.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Creative language generation by NLG has been hypothesized since the field's origins.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] A recent pioneer in the area is Phillip Parker, who has developed an arsenal of algorithms capable of automatically generating textbooks, crossword puzzles, poems and books on topics ranging from bookbinding to cataracts.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] The advent of large pretrained transformer-based language models such as GPT-3 has also enabled breakthroughs, with such models demonstrating recognizable ability for creating-writing tasks.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] A related area of NLG application is computational humor production.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] JAPE (Joke Analysis and Production Engine) is one of the earliest large, automated humor production systems that uses a hand-coded template-based approach to create punning riddles for children.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] HAHAcronym creates humorous reinterpretations of any given acronym, as well as proposing new fitting acronyms given some keywords.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Despite progresses, many challenges remain in producing automated creative and humorous content that rival human output.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] In an experiment for generating satirical headlines, outputs of their best BERT-based model were perceived as funny 9.4% of the time (while real headlines from *The Onion* were 38.4%) and a GPT-2 model fine-tuned on satirical headlines achieved 6.9%.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] It has been pointed out that two main issues with humor-generation systems are the lack of annotated data sets and the lack of formal evaluation methods, which could be applicable to other creative content generation.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Some have argued relative to other applications, there has been a lack of attention to creative aspects of language production within NLG.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] NLG researchers stand to benefit from insights into what constitutes creative language production, as well as structural features of narrative that have the potential to improve NLG output even in data-to-text systems.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] As in other scientific fields, NLG researchers need to test how well their systems, modules, and algorithms work.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] An ultimate goal is how useful NLG systems are at helping people, which is the first of the above techniques.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] However, task-based evaluations are time-consuming and expensive, and can be difficult to carry out (especially if they require subjects with specialised expertise, such as doctors).
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Hence (as in other areas of NLP) task-based evaluations are the exception, not the norm.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Recently researchers are assessing how well human-ratings and metrics correlate with (predict) task-based evaluations.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Work is being conducted in the context of Generation Challenges shared-task events.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] Initial results suggest that human ratings are much better than metrics in this regard.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] In other words, human ratings usually do predict task-effectiveness at least to some degree (although there are exceptions), while ratings produced by metrics often do not predict task-effectiveness well.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] In any case, human ratings are the most popular evaluation technique in NLG; this is contrast to machine translation, where metrics are widely used.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] An AI can be graded on *faithfulness* to its training data or, alternatively, on *factuality*.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] A response that reflects the training data but not reality is faithful but not factual.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] A confident but unfaithful response is a *hallucination*.
[src:image-captioning/natural-language-generation] In Natural Language Processing, a hallucination is often defined as "generated content that is nonsensical or unfaithful to the provided source content".
